{"title_page": "Nam Ou", "text_new": "The '''Nam Ou''' ([[Lao language|Laotian]]: \u0e99\u0ec9\u0eb3\u0ead\u0eb9 {{IPA-lo|n\u00e2\u02d0m \u00f9\u02d0|}}, [[Literal translation|literally]]: \"rice bowl river\") is one of the most important rivers of [[Laos]]. It runs 448&nbsp;km from [[Phongsaly Province]] to [[Luang Prabang Province]][https://web.archive.org/web/20080409150525/http://www.un.int/lao/laos_in_brief.htm]. The river rises in Muang Ou Nua,near the Lao-Chinese border and traverses the northern Laos mountains and gorges until meeting the Mekong River in Ban Pak Ou.<ref>{{cite web |last1=The Editors of Encyclopedia Britannica |title=Ou River |url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Ou-River-Laos |website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref> Along with the [[Mekong]], the Nam Ou is the only natural channel suitable for large-draft [[ship transport|boat transportation]]. The Nam Ou is one of the 12 principal tributaries of the Mekong River.<ref>{{cite web |last1=The Editors of Encyclopedia Britannica |title=Ou River |url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Ou-River-Laos |website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref> The river has a total area of nearly 26,000 km\u00b2.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River Basin Profile: Summary Document |url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/943151502977494355/pdf/118746-WP-Nam-Ou-Basin-Profile-English-language-PUBLIC.pdf |website=World Bank |publisher=International Finance Corporation}}</ref> Near its confluence with the Mekong are the [[Pak Ou Caves]], famous for their [[Buddharupa|Buddha statues]]. The river is also surrounded by limestone karts, forests, and valleys. The river supports Lao rice cultivation. The Nam Ou placed in the top 80th percentile for river health according to the [[Mekong River Commission]]\u2019s aquatic health index.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River Basin Profile: Summary Document |url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/943151502977494355/pdf/118746-WP-Nam-Ou-Basin-Profile-English-language-PUBLIC.pdf |website=World Bank |publisher=International Finance Corporation}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2014 12 Thailand Laos-451.JPG|thumb|Dam Construckion at Nam Ou River]]\n\n[[File:nam ou 2.jpg|thumb|A ferryboat between [[Nong Kiau]] and [[Luang Prabang]].]]\n[[File:nam ou 1.jpg|thumb|The 'Nam Ou' is an important transportation route in Laos.]]\n\n{{commons category|Nam Ou}}\n\n{{coord|20|03|N|102|13|E|display=title|region:LA_type:river_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Laos]]\n[[Category:Tributaries of the Mekong River]]\n== Ecology ==\nThe Nam Ou river provides a habitat to 84 species of fish, with 29 of these species inhabiting the Nam Ou exclusively.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River |url=https://www.internationalrivers.org/campaigns/nam-ou-river |website=International Rivers}}</ref> The northern portion of the river flows through [[Phou Den Din National Protected Area]] (NPA) which is home to Asian elephants, Indochinese tigers, white-cheeked gibbons and large antlered muntjac \u2013 all endangered species.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River Basin Profile: Summary Document |url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/943151502977494355/pdf/118746-WP-Nam-Ou-Basin-Profile-English-language-PUBLIC.pdf |website=World Bank |publisher=International Finance Corporation}}</ref> The river also provides a habitat to riverine birds, otters, and reptiles, with many categorized as endangered by the IUCN red list.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River |url=https://www.internationalrivers.org/campaigns/nam-ou-river |website=International Rivers}}</ref>\n\n== Cultural Importance ==\nDifferent ethnic minorities villages with generations of history are located on the river and rely of the river for survival. This includes collecting resources from the river and surrounding forests for income, food, and spiritual practices.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River |url=https://www.internationalrivers.org/campaigns/nam-ou-river |website=International Rivers}}</ref> The river and surrounding villages have also become a tourist destination of hikers, tour groups, and kayakers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River |url=https://www.internationalrivers.org/campaigns/nam-ou-river |website=International Rivers}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Phonsaly]] provice of Laos is home to three main ethnic groups including the [[Khmu]] who account for 22% of the population, the [[Songsiri]] (18%), and the [[Akha people|Akha]] (27%). The Khmu are the largest ethnic group in [[Oudomxay]] with 59% of the population, the [[Lue people|Lue]] account for 10% of the population, and the [[Hmong people|Hmong]] make up 14% of the provincial population. The Khmu are also the main ethnic group in [[Luang Prabang]] with 47% of the population, the [[Lao people|Lao]] ethnic group makes up 29% of the population and the Hmong account for 16% of the population.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River Basin Profile: Summary Document |url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/943151502977494355/pdf/118746-WP-Nam-Ou-Basin-Profile-English-language-PUBLIC.pdf |website=World Bank |publisher=International Finance Corporation}}</ref> All six of these ethnic groups have different geographical origins, spiritual and religious practices, and occupational preferences/expertise.\n\n\n== Development of the River ==\nThe Nam Ou River is the site of the Nam Ou River Cascade Dams which are a series of seven dams in different sites along the river.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ingram |first1=Elizabeth |title=Second phase of 1,156-MW Nam Ou hydro project kicks off in Laos |url=https://www.hydroreview.com/2016/05/04/second-phase-of-1-156-mw-nam-ou-hydro-project-kicks-off-in-laos/#gref |agency=Hydro Review |date=2016-05-04}}</ref> Eighty-nine villages surrounding the river are expected to be relocated by the project.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River |url=https://www.internationalrivers.org/campaigns/nam-ou-river |website=International Rivers}}</ref> There are concerns that the project may cause of negative impact on the local animal and plant species.\n\nDevelopment on the Nam Ou river and other hydropower projects on other tributaries or directly on the Mekong River have affected characteristics of the river and surrounding land. The Mekong River Commission has occupied a precarious position of asking for patience to assess the consequences of hydropower projects while also previously stating the the abundance of hydropower projects in the region may negatively affect river ecosystems and river sustainability.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Board |first1=Jack |title='The colour is blue\u2019: Strange changes to Mekong River as hydropower dams and climate change make their mark |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/mekong-river-colour-xayaburi-dam-laos-hydroelectric-power-12244064 |agency=Channel News Asia |date=2020-01-12}}</ref> Thousands Laotian villagers have been relocated as a result of hydropower development projects. Villagers in areas affected by hydropower projects are relocated by the Laotian government. Resettlement sites often include modernized towns with amenities like roads, bridges, temples, trading markets, and health centers and schools nearby.<ref>{{cite web |title=Power Construction Corporation of China: Laos Sustainability Report |url=https://www.powerchina.cn/attach/0/80534e1639394910af822ddcfd51670a.pdf |website=PowerChina |publisher=PowerChina}}</ref> Some of these have been built by contractors and developers of hydropower projects. Some villagers have trouble readjusting to new locations because they lose access to fish, river-bank gardens, and edible river vegetation.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Saimok |title=The Loss of the Ou River |url=https://focusweb.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/River_Ou.pdf |website=Focus on the Global South}}</ref>\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Laos-river-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Nam Ou''' ([[Lao language|Laotian]]: \u0e99\u0ec9\u0eb3\u0ead\u0eb9 {{IPA-lo|n\u00e2\u02d0m \u00f9\u02d0|}}, [[Literal translation|literally]]: \"rice bowl river\") is one of the most important rivers of [[Laos]]. It runs 448&nbsp;km from [[Phongsaly Province]] to [[Luang Prabang Province]][https://web.archive.org/web/20080409150525/http://www.un.int/lao/laos_in_brief.htm]. The river rises in Muang Ou Nua,near the Lao-Chinese border and traverses the northern Laos mountains and gorges until meeting the Mekong River in Ban Pak Ou.<ref>{{cite web |last1=The Editors of Encyclopedia Britannica |title=Ou River |url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Ou-River-Laos |website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref> Along with the [[Mekong]], the Nam Ou is the only natural channel suitable for large-draft [[ship transport|boat transportation]]. The Nam Ou is one of the 12 principal tributaries of the Mekong River.<ref>{{cite web |last1=The Editors of Encyclopedia Britannica |title=Ou River |url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Ou-River-Laos |website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref> The river has a total area of nearly 26,000 km\u00b2.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River Basin Profile: Summary Document |url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/943151502977494355/pdf/118746-WP-Nam-Ou-Basin-Profile-English-language-PUBLIC.pdf |website=World Bank |publisher=International Finance Corporation}}</ref> Near its confluence with the Mekong are the [[Pak Ou Caves]], famous for their [[Buddharupa|Buddha statues]]. The river is also surrounded by limestone karts, forests, and valleys. The river supports Lao rice cultivation. The Nam Ou placed in the top 80th percentile for river health according to the [[Mekong River Commission]]\u2019s aquatic health index.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River Basin Profile: Summary Document |url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/943151502977494355/pdf/118746-WP-Nam-Ou-Basin-Profile-English-language-PUBLIC.pdf |website=World Bank |publisher=International Finance Corporation}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2014 12 Thailand Laos-451.JPG|thumb|Dam Construckion at Nam Ou River]]\n\n[[File:nam ou 2.jpg|thumb|A ferryboat between [[Nong Kiau]] and [[Luang Prabang]].]]\n[[File:nam ou 1.jpg|thumb|The 'Nam Ou' is an important transportation route in Laos.]]\n\n{{commons category|Nam Ou}}\n\n{{coord|20|03|N|102|13|E|display=title|region:LA_type:river_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Laos]]\n[[Category:Tributaries of the Mekong River]]\n== Ecology ==\nThe Nam Ou river provides a habitat to 84 species of fish, with 29 of these species inhabiting the Nam Ou exclusively.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River |url=https://www.internationalrivers.org/campaigns/nam-ou-river |website=International Rivers}}</ref> The northern portion of the river flows through [[Phou Den Din National Protected Area]] (NPA) which is home to Asian elephants, Indochinese tigers, white-cheeked gibbons and large antlered muntjac \u2013 all endangered species.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River Basin Profile: Summary Document |url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/943151502977494355/pdf/118746-WP-Nam-Ou-Basin-Profile-English-language-PUBLIC.pdf |website=World Bank |publisher=International Finance Corporation}}</ref> The river also provides a habitat to riverine birds, otters, and reptiles, with many categorized as endangered by the IUCN red list.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River |url=https://www.internationalrivers.org/campaigns/nam-ou-river |website=International Rivers}}</ref>\n\n== Cultural Importance ==\nDifferent ethnic minorities villages with generations of history are located on the river and rely of the river for survival. This includes collecting resources from the river and surrounding forests for income, food, and spiritual practices.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River |url=https://www.internationalrivers.org/campaigns/nam-ou-river |website=International Rivers}}</ref> The river and surrounding villages have also become a tourist destination of hikers, tour groups, and kayakers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River |url=https://www.internationalrivers.org/campaigns/nam-ou-river |website=International Rivers}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Phonsaly]] provice of Laos is home to three main ethnic groups including the [[Khmu]] who account for 22% of the population, the [[Songsiri]] (18%), and the [[Akha]] (27%). The Khmu are the largest ethnic group in [[Oudomxay]] with 59% of the population, the [[Lue]] account for 10% of the population, and the [[Hmong]] make up 14% of the provincial population. The Khmu are also the main ethnic group in [[Luang Prabang]] with 47% of the population, the [[Lao]] ethnic group makes up 29% of the population and the Hmong account for 16% of the population.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River Basin Profile: Summary Document |url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/943151502977494355/pdf/118746-WP-Nam-Ou-Basin-Profile-English-language-PUBLIC.pdf |website=World Bank |publisher=International Finance Corporation}}</ref> All six of these ethnic groups have different geographical origins, spiritual and religious practices, and occupational preferences/expertise.\n\n\n== Development of the River ==\nThe Nam Ou River is the site of the Nam Ou River Cascade Dams which are a series of seven dams in different sites along the river.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ingram |first1=Elizabeth |title=Second phase of 1,156-MW Nam Ou hydro project kicks off in Laos |url=https://www.hydroreview.com/2016/05/04/second-phase-of-1-156-mw-nam-ou-hydro-project-kicks-off-in-laos/#gref |agency=Hydro Review |date=2016-05-04}}</ref> Eighty-nine villages surrounding the river are expected to be relocated by the project.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nam Ou River |url=https://www.internationalrivers.org/campaigns/nam-ou-river |website=International Rivers}}</ref> There are concerns that the project may cause of negative impact on the local animal and plant species.\n\nDevelopment on the Nam Ou river and other hydropower projects on other tributaries or directly on the Mekong River have affected characteristics of the river and surrounding land. The Mekong River Commission has occupied a precarious position of asking for patience to assess the consequences of hydropower projects while also previously stating the the abundance of hydropower projects in the region may negatively affect river ecosystems and river sustainability.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Board |first1=Jack |title='The colour is blue\u2019: Strange changes to Mekong River as hydropower dams and climate change make their mark |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/mekong-river-colour-xayaburi-dam-laos-hydroelectric-power-12244064 |agency=Channel News Asia |date=2020-01-12}}</ref> Thousands Laotian villagers have been relocated as a result of hydropower development projects. Villagers in areas affected by hydropower projects are relocated by the Laotian government. Resettlement sites often include modernized towns with amenities like roads, bridges, temples, trading markets, and health centers and schools nearby.<ref>{{cite web |title=Power Construction Corporation of China: Laos Sustainability Report |url=https://www.powerchina.cn/attach/0/80534e1639394910af822ddcfd51670a.pdf |website=PowerChina |publisher=PowerChina}}</ref> Some of these have been built by contractors and developers of hydropower projects. Some villagers have trouble readjusting to new locations because they lose access to fish, river-bank gardens, and edible river vegetation.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Saimok |title=The Loss of the Ou River |url=https://focusweb.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/River_Ou.pdf |website=Focus on the Global South}}</ref>\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Laos-river-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Akha\u2192Akha people,Lue\u2192Lue people,Hmong\u2192Hmong people,Lao\u2192Lao people", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nam_Ou"}
