{"title_page": "Darius Shu", "text_new": "{{short description|UK cinematographer (born 1994)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Darius Shu\n| image         = Darius Tribeca2 (1) copy.jpg\n| image_upright = \n| caption       = Shu at the red carpet world premiere of His Hands at [[Tribeca Film Festival]] 2019\n| other_names   = \n| birth_date    = {{birth-date and age|5 May 1994}}\n| education     = Arts University Bournemouth\n| occupation    = Cinematographer\n| years_active  = 2013-present\n| notable_works = ''His Hands'' <br> ''Secret Child''\n| spouse        = \n| website       = {{URL|https://www.dariusshu.com/}}\n}}\n'''Darius Shu''' (born 5 May 1994) is a British [[cinematographer]], best known for his work on the films ''[[His Hands (film)|His Hands]]'' and ''[[Secret Child]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dariusshu.com/about|title=About {{!}} DARIUS SHU {{!}} Director of Photography|website=dariusshu 2.0|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\nA recipient of more than five Best Cinematography awards, Shu has had back to back award-winning films over the recent years. His directorial debut short film ''[[His Hands (film)|His Hands]]'' with [[Arron Blake]] world premiered at [[Tribeca Film Festival]] 2019, for which the film was nominated for Best Narrative Short.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/showbiz/2019/04/29/malaysian-co-directed-low-budget-silent-film-makes-debut-in-new-yorks-tribe/1748058|title=Malaysian co-directed, low-budget silent film makes debut in New York\u2019s Tribeca Film Festival {{!}} Malay Mail|last=Chalil|first=Melanie|website=www.malaymail.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.qweerist.com/entertainment/his-hands-short-film-tribeca/|title=Short film shot on \u00a3400 budget to get Tribeca premiere|date=2019-04-08|website=QWEERIST|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nFrom the age of 3, Shu started drawing and painting and attended art classes. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inreallife.my/career-skills/behind-the-scenes-the-struggles-between-hardwork-and-success-darius-shus-story/|title=Behind the Scenes: Struggling from Hardwork to Success; Darius Shu\u2019s Story|last=enquiries|first=IRL Author This writer has chosen to remain anonymous For any|last2=Us!|first2=Please Head Over to Our Contact Page to Get in Touch with|date=2018-07-06|website=In Real Life|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> By age 13, Shu also had passion for interior design in which he started decorating his own home and room as he finds complementing colours fascinating. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inreallife.my/career-skills/behind-the-scenes-the-struggles-between-hardwork-and-success-darius-shus-story/|title=Behind the Scenes: Struggling from Hardwork to Success; Darius Shu\u2019s Story|last=enquiries|first=IRL Author This writer has chosen to remain anonymous For any|last2=Us!|first2=Please Head Over to Our Contact Page to Get in Touch with|date=2018-07-06|website=In Real Life|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>Shu also had an interest in songwriting and began writing songs as his mother taught him how to play the piano.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inreallife.my/career-skills/behind-the-scenes-the-struggles-between-hardwork-and-success-darius-shus-story/|title=Behind the Scenes: Struggling from Hardwork to Success; Darius Shu\u2019s Story|last=enquiries|first=IRL Author This writer has chosen to remain anonymous For any|last2=Us!|first2=Please Head Over to Our Contact Page to Get in Touch with|date=2018-07-06|website=In Real Life|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Subsequently Shu enrolled in University of the West of England, [[Bristol]] where he studied broadcasting, journalism and media for his degree after finishing high school. While studying his degree, Shu developed a passion for [[photography]]. He began to shoot and edit his own films with friends and developed his interest for cinematography.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{Cite web|url=https://inreallife.my/career-skills/behind-the-scenes-the-struggles-between-hardwork-and-success-darius-shus-story/|title=Behind the Scenes: Struggling from Hardwork to Success; Darius Shu\u2019s Story|date=2018-07-06|website=In Real Life|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> Shu also ventured into doing fashion photography. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inreallife.my/career-skills/behind-the-scenes-the-struggles-between-hardwork-and-success-darius-shus-story/|title=Behind the Scenes: Struggling from Hardwork to Success; Darius Shu\u2019s Story|last=enquiries|first=IRL Author This writer has chosen to remain anonymous For any|last2=Us!|first2=Please Head Over to Our Contact Page to Get in Touch with|date=2018-07-06|website=In Real Life|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nAfter university, Shu pursued his Masters in Film Production in Cinematography at Arts University Bournemouth in [[Poole]], [[Dorset]]. He mentioned that his inspirations were [[Roger Deakins]], [[Christopher Nolan]] and [[Denis Villeneuve]].<ref name=autogenerated4/> Shu now resides in [[London]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dariusshu.com/about|title=About {{!}} DARIUS SHU {{!}} Director of Photography|website=dariusshu 2.0|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nAfter graduating his bachelor's degree, Shu started shooting for luxury fashion magazines, music videos and documentaries.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> His love for filmmaking made him dive into cinematography.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> At the Bournemouth Film School, he had the opportunity to shoot ''Pardaa'' (2017) with director Kajri Babbar. The film became a Semi-Finalist at the 44th [[Student Academy Awards]]. It premiered at Aesthetica Short Film Festival in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aub.ac.uk/courses-category/course-news-category/aub-film-pardaa-receives-success-film-festivals/|title=Award winning AUB film Pardaa receives success at Film Festivals|date=2017-08-04|website=Arts University Bournemouth|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\nShu was approached by producer Gordon Lewis and director Yew Weng Ho to shoot his new film ''[[Secret Child]]'' in 2017. The film is based on Gordon Lewis' bestselling book, ''Secret Child''. It starred [[Fiona Glascott]] ([[Brooklyn]], [[Fantastic Beasts: The Crimes of Grindelwald]]), Austin Taylor ([[My Cousin Rachel (2017 film)|My Cousin Rachel]], [[Doctor Who]]) and [[Aaron McCusker]] ([[Bohemian Rhapsody (film)|Bohemian Rhapsody]], [[Shameless (British TV series)|Shameless]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/culture/entertainment/secret-child-gordon-lewis|title=\"Secret Child\" - short film portrays pain of growing up in an Irish mother and babies home|date=2018-05-17|website=IrishCentral.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> ''Secret Child'' tells the true story in the 1950s that deals with a young boy hidden away from the world in a home for unmarried mothers called Regina Coeli in Dublin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25989021-secret-child|title=Secret Child|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.secretchild.com/the-story|title=Gordon Lewis {{!}} Official Website|last=|first=|date=|website=Secret Child|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> The film was a breakthrough success for Shu as it won more than 20 international awards. It had its world premiere at the [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre|Chinese Theatre]] in [[Hollywood]] at the [[HollyShorts Film Festival]] 2018 and receive a nomination for Best Period Piece.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hollyshorts.com/filmmakers-2018|title=Official Selections 2018 \u2014|website=www.hollyshorts.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> \n\nFor its London premiere at the New Renaissance Film Festival 2018, ''[[Secret Child]]'' won Best Debut Film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newrenaissancefilmfest.com/winners-nrff-london-2018|title=WINNERS \u2013 NEW RENAISSANCE LONDON 2018 \u00ab New Renaissance Film Festival|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Producer Gordon Lewis is currently in talks to turn ''Secret Child'' into a [[television series]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/showbiz/2018/06/08/uk-based-malaysian-cinematographer-earning-raves-with-film-on-secret-cathol/1640021|title=UK-based Malaysian cinematographer earning raves with film on secret Catholic hostel life {{!}} Malay Mail|last=Chalil|first=Melanie|website=www.malaymail.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/movies/movie-news/article36897505.ece|title=\u2018I couldn\u2019t have published this memoir if my mother was alive - it was too painful for her\u2019 - Irish man raised in mother and baby home|website=independent|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\nLater that year, Shu reunited with Kajri Babbar for her second television-film, [[ZEE5]] Original, ''Khoj'' (2018) filming in both UK and India with [[Bollywood]] actress Zara Khan.\n\nThe film premiered at [[Cannes Film Festival]] and went on to stream on [[ZEE5]], India's largest streaming channel[[Cannes Film Festival|.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/kajri-babbars-short-film-to-release-on-lohri/1456398|title=Kajri Babbar's short film to release on Lohri|website=www.outlookindia.com|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-zee5-announces-kajri-babbar-s-award-winning-short-film-khoj-2706987|title=ZEE5 announces Kajri Babbar's award winning short film 'Khoj'|last=Team|first=DNA Web|date=2019-01-12|website=DNA India|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n[[File:His hands Tribeca 3 (1).jpg|alt=|thumb|344x344px|Shu (left) with Arron Blake and Philip Brisebois at the red carpet premiere of ''His Hands'' at [[Tribeca Film Festival]] 2019, New York]]\nIn 2018, Shu team up with [[Arron Blake]] and they both co-directed, wrote, and produced ''[[His Hands (film)|His Hands]] (2019),'' with Shu shooting the film as the cinematographer. This was their directorial debut and the first film they made together starring Arron Blake and Philip Brisebois. ''His Hands'' had its world premiere at [[Robert De Niro]]'s [[Tribeca Film Festival]] 2019 in [[New York City|New York]]. The film received nomination for Best Narrative Short.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/film/2019/4/26/two-men-have-psychosexual-encounter-new-short-film|title=Two Men Have a Psychosexual Encounter in New Short Film|date=2019-04-26|website=www.advocate.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> The film created a whole new experience as it was a silent psychological thriller, using only the power of visual storytelling and cinematography.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{Cite web|url=http://attitude.co.uk/article/his-hands-review-an-erotic-and-unsettling-short-film-of-striking-power/19976/|title='His Hands' review: 'An erotic and unsettling short film of striking power'|date=2019-01-02|website=Attitude.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> It tells the story of two men meeting for the most unusual unanimity of their lives as it touches themes such as sexuality, loneliness, identity and ageism.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated3\" />  The film was applauded as a cinematic masterpiece as it was made on a low budget of \u00a3400, with no dialogue delivery throughout the film and using only natural light during filming.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.londonlive.co.uk/news/2019-05-16/film-with-budget-of-400-premiere-s|title=Film with budget of \u00a3400 premiered at world leading film festival|date=2019-05-16|website=London Live|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> The film was released on [[Prime Video|Amazon Prime Video]] and has received rave 5 star reviews from the public with critical acclaim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/His-Hands-Arron-Blake/product-reviews/B07WPG85QK/ref=cm_cr_dp_d_show_all_btm?ie=UTF8&reviewerType=all_reviews|title=Amazon.co.uk:Customer reviews: His Hands|website=www.amazon.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Shu team up to shoot a film with director [[Rikki Beadle-Blair|Rikki-Beadle Blair]], MBE. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BxrgHSvnu2z/|title=Bridge The Moon on Instagram: \u201cOur producers held our 1st meeting @bafta to kickstart pre-production for our upcoming film \u2018Tainted\u2019. \u2800 \u2800 Directed by the inimitable\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> He has also shot a commercial for [[Chanel]] and [[Coach New York|Coach]] where he was flown over to New York to film with seven celebrities from [[Southeast Asia|South East Asia]]. Shu attended Chanel's prestigious fashion show during [[Paris Fashion Week]] in France to shoot for Chanel with singer-songwriter [[Yuna (singer)|Yuna]] and The Laterals magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B3_0JUXl8ug/|title=DARIUS SHU on Instagram: \"ACT II: THE STREET \u2800 @chanelofficial @thelaterals featuring @yuna. \u2800 #HANDBAGCHANEL19 \u2800 \u2800 Cinematography by Darius Shu\u2800 Produced by\u2026\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\nLater that year, Shu reunited with director Yew Weng Ho on a new [[dyslexia]] film, ''Mical (2020)''. It follows the true story of Pat and Mike Jones on the struggles and journey of being dyslexic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.micalthefilm.com/|title=Mical {{!}} Official Film Site|website=Mical The Film|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> The film is to create awareness on dyslexia and to support the Dyslexia Trust.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.micalthefilm.com/|title=Mical {{!}} Official Film Site|website=Mical The Film|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Shu is currently working with [[Shiva Raichandani]] on his new British-Asian drama-musical film ''Queer Parivaar'' based on an interfaith queer wedding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.queerparivaar.co.uk/team|title=TEAM|website=Queer Parivaar|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n== Recognition ==\n\n[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]] magazine, reviewed Shu's film ''[[His Hands (film)|His Hands]] (2019)'' calling, \"the cinematography is beautiful, modern and stylish. ''His Hands'' is a powerful film that says a lot without \u201csaying\u201d anything at all. Its themes and images converge to create a stylish, dynamic thriller; Blake and Shu cleverly make use of colours, images, ideas in place of speech, and the film has a unique energy all the better for it.\"<ref name=autogenerated2 /> [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]] praised Shu as, \"a cinematographer who shoots to make things and people stand out.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/lifestyle/people/2018/06/27/cinematographer-darius-shu|title=Cinematographer Darius Shu shoots to make things and people stand out {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> [[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] magazine pointed out that, \"the cinematography of ''His Hands'' offers an unnerving experience through dark, haunting images with no dialogue.\"<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\n[[Mark Gatiss]], the producer of [[Netflix]]-[[BBC]] television series [[Dracula (2020 TV series)|Dracula]] and [[Sherlock (TV series)|Sherlock]], reviewed Shu's film ''His Hands'' as, ''\"A beguilingly beautiful gem, Arron Blake and Darius Shu's His Hands defies easy analysis. Shot through with strange, homoerotic melancholy it's ravishing to look at and haunts the memory long after.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldofbuzz.com/with-only-rm2000-msian-directors-debut-film-was-selected-for-robert-de-niros-film-festival/|title=This M\u2019sian Director\u2019s Debut Film Only Cost RM2,000 But Was Selected For Robert De Niro\u2019s Film Festival! - WORLD OF BUZZ|last=Ng|first=Scott|date=2019-05-01|website=www.worldofbuzz.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/lifestyle/entertainment/2019/04/30/darius-shu-his-hands-tribeca-film-festival|title=Malaysian Darius Shu's 'His Hands' goes to NY's Tribeca Film Fest {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\nFilm Threat praised Shu's work as, \"glorious cinematography, beautifully well shot, exuding a mysterious atmosphere in each frame\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/his-hands/|title=His Hands {{!}} Film Threat|date=2019-04-27|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> while Unsettled Magazine called ''His Hands'', \"a masterpiece built on suspense and appealing imagery.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/entertainmentmovies/malaysian-co-directed-low-budget-silent-film-makes-debut-in-new-yorks-tribeca-film-festival/ar-BBWoply?li=AAaD1A0|title=Malaysian co-directed, low-budget silent film makes debut in New York\u2019s Tribeca Film Festival|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\nUK Film Review stated that there were \"splendid visual moments\" in ''His Hands'' and \"Shu turns in some excellent cinematography as well as some clever framing.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukfilmreview.co.uk/post/his-hands-short-film|title=His Hands short film|last=Olson|first=Chris|date=2018-11-13|website=UK Film Review|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nShu made his first live television appearance in an interview on [[London Live (TV channel)|London Live]] after the success of [[Tribeca Film Festival]].<ref name=autogenerated1 /> He has also appeared in an extensive newspaper coverage in the mainstream media in [[Southeast Asia|South East Asia]] and the UK.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dariusshu.com/news|title=News {{!}} DARIUS SHU {{!}} Director of Photography|website=dariusshu 2.0|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n'''Films'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Director\n!Notes\n|-\n|2016\n|''Grief''\n|Caspar Muller\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\n|-\n|2016\n|''Bulletproof''\n|Darius Shu \n|-\n|2016\n|''Pardaa''\n|Kajri Babbar\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''White Balance: The Grape''\n|Tashita Mukherji\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''Narcissus Revisited''\n|Caspar Muller\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''Secret Child''\n|Yewweng Ho\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''Khoj''\n|Kajri Babbar\n|TV movie\n|-\n|2019\n|''His Hands''\n|Arron Blake, Darius Shu\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''Tainted''\n|[[Rikki Beadle-Blair]]\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''Mical''\n|Yewweng Ho\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''Queer Parivaar''\n|[[Shiva Raichandani]] \n|\n|-\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n\n=== Film festivals ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Festival\n!Category\n!Work\n!Result\n|-\n|2017\n|Aesthetica Short Film Festival\n|Nahemi Short Film Award \n| rowspan=\"3\" |''Pardaa''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2017\n|Calcutta International Cult Film Festival\n|Best Short Film\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2017\n|Sydney Indie Film Festival\n|Best Drama\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n|[[HollyShorts Film Festival|Hollyshorts Film Festival]]\n|Best Period Piece\n| rowspan=\"15\" |''Secret Child''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|Alternative Film Festival\n|Best Period Piece\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2018\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Los Angeles Independent Film Festival Awards\n|Best Cinematography\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n|Best Drama Short\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|New Renaissance Film Festival\n|Best Debut Film\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2018\n|Gold Movie Awards\n|Best Short Film\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Festigious International Film Festival\n|Best Cinematography\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Narrative Short\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2018\n|European Cinematography Awards\n|Best Short Film\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Bucharest ShortCut Cinefest\n|Best Cinematography\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Film\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2018\n|Kerry Film Festival\n|Best Short Film\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2018\n|Largo Film Awards\n|Best Cinematography\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2018\n|Oniros Film Awards\n|Best Cinematography\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2018\n|Sydney Indie Film Festival\n|Best Film\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2018\n|Cefal\u00f9 Film Festival\n|Best Short Film\n|''Bulletproof''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Cannes Film Festival]]\n|Short Film Corner\n|''Khoj''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2018\n|Gold Movie Awards\n|Best Cinematography\n| rowspan=\"6\" |''His Hands''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Tribeca Film Festival]]\n|Best Narrative Short\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2019\n|Canada Shorts Film Festival\n|Award of Excellence\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2019\n|London International Motion Pictures Award\n|Best Narrative / Fiction UK Short Film\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2019\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Queen Palm International Film Festival\n|Best Cinematography \n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Short Film - Silent|Best Short Film - Silent\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2020\n|Maryland International Film Festival\n|Best Short Film\n|''Mical''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm8954266/?ref_=ttfc_fc_cr5 Darius Shu] on [[IMDb|IMDB]]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/dariusshu5 Darius Shu] on [[Instagram]]\n* [https://www.twitter.com/dariusshu Darius Shu] on [[Twitter]]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/dariusshu Darius Shu] on [[Facebook]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shu, Darius}}\n\n[[Category: 1994 births]]\n[[Category:English cinematographers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Film directors from London]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:People from London]]\n[[Category:British cinematographers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|UK cinematographer (born 1994)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Darius Shu\n| image         = Darius Tribeca2 (1) copy.jpg\n| image_upright = \n| caption       = Shu at the red carpet world premiere of His Hands at [[Tribeca Film Festival]] 2019\n| other_names   = \n| birth_date    = {{birth-date and age|5 May 1994}}\n| education     = Arts University Bournemouth\n| occupation    = Cinematographer\n| years_active  = 2013-present\n| notable_works = ''His Hands'' <br> ''Secret Child''\n| spouse        = \n| website       = {{URL|https://www.dariusshu.com/}}\n}}\n'''Darius Shu''' (born 5 May 1994) is a British [[cinematographer]], best known for his work on the films ''[[His Hands (film)|His Hands]]'' and ''[[Secret Child]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dariusshu.com/about|title=About {{!}} DARIUS SHU {{!}} Director of Photography|website=dariusshu 2.0|language=en|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\nA recipient of more than five Best Cinematography awards, Shu has had back to back award-winning films over the recent years. His directorial debut short film ''[[His Hands (film)|His Hands]]'' with [[Arron Blake]] world premiered at [[Tribeca Film Festival]] 2019, for which the film was nominated for Best Narrative Short.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/showbiz/2019/04/29/malaysian-co-directed-low-budget-silent-film-makes-debut-in-new-yorks-tribe/1748058|title=Malaysian co-directed, low-budget silent film makes debut in New York\u2019s Tribeca Film Festival {{!}} Malay Mail|last=Chalil|first=Melanie|website=www.malaymail.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.qweerist.com/entertainment/his-hands-short-film-tribeca/|title=Short film shot on \u00a3400 budget to get Tribeca premiere|date=2019-04-08|website=QWEERIST|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nFrom the age of 3, Shu started drawing and painting and attended art classes. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inreallife.my/career-skills/behind-the-scenes-the-struggles-between-hardwork-and-success-darius-shus-story/|title=Behind the Scenes: Struggling from Hardwork to Success; Darius Shu\u2019s Story|last=enquiries|first=IRL Author This writer has chosen to remain anonymous For any|last2=Us!|first2=Please Head Over to Our Contact Page to Get in Touch with|date=2018-07-06|website=In Real Life|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> By age 13, Shu also had passion for interior design in which he started decorating his own home and room as he finds complementing colours fascinating. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inreallife.my/career-skills/behind-the-scenes-the-struggles-between-hardwork-and-success-darius-shus-story/|title=Behind the Scenes: Struggling from Hardwork to Success; Darius Shu\u2019s Story|last=enquiries|first=IRL Author This writer has chosen to remain anonymous For any|last2=Us!|first2=Please Head Over to Our Contact Page to Get in Touch with|date=2018-07-06|website=In Real Life|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>Shu also had an interest in songwriting and began writing songs as his mother taught him how to play the piano.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inreallife.my/career-skills/behind-the-scenes-the-struggles-between-hardwork-and-success-darius-shus-story/|title=Behind the Scenes: Struggling from Hardwork to Success; Darius Shu\u2019s Story|last=enquiries|first=IRL Author This writer has chosen to remain anonymous For any|last2=Us!|first2=Please Head Over to Our Contact Page to Get in Touch with|date=2018-07-06|website=In Real Life|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Subsequently Shu enrolled in University of the West of England, [[Bristol]] where he studied broadcasting, journalism and media for his degree after finishing high school. While studying his degree, Shu developed a passion for [[photography]]. He began to shoot and edit his own films with friends and developed his interest for cinematography.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{Cite web|url=https://inreallife.my/career-skills/behind-the-scenes-the-struggles-between-hardwork-and-success-darius-shus-story/|title=Behind the Scenes: Struggling from Hardwork to Success; Darius Shu\u2019s Story|date=2018-07-06|website=In Real Life|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> Shu also ventured into doing fashion photography. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inreallife.my/career-skills/behind-the-scenes-the-struggles-between-hardwork-and-success-darius-shus-story/|title=Behind the Scenes: Struggling from Hardwork to Success; Darius Shu\u2019s Story|last=enquiries|first=IRL Author This writer has chosen to remain anonymous For any|last2=Us!|first2=Please Head Over to Our Contact Page to Get in Touch with|date=2018-07-06|website=In Real Life|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nAfter university, Shu pursued his Masters in Film Production in Cinematography at Arts University Bournemouth in [[Poole]], [[Dorset]]. He mentioned that his inspirations are [[Roger Deakins]], [[Christopher Nolan]] and [[Denis Villeneuve]].<ref name=autogenerated4/> Shu now resides in [[London]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dariusshu.com/about|title=About {{!}} DARIUS SHU {{!}} Director of Photography|website=dariusshu 2.0|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nAfter graduating his bachelor's degree, Shu started shooting for luxury fashion magazines, music videos and documentaries.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> His love for filmmaking made him dive into cinematography.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> At the Bournemouth Film School, he had the opportunity to shoot ''Pardaa'' (2017) with director Kajri Babbar. The film became a Semi-Finalist at the 44th [[Student Academy Awards]]. It premiered at Aesthetica Short Film Festival in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aub.ac.uk/courses-category/course-news-category/aub-film-pardaa-receives-success-film-festivals/|title=Award winning AUB film Pardaa receives success at Film Festivals|date=2017-08-04|website=Arts University Bournemouth|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\nShu was approached by producer Gordon Lewis and director Yew Weng Ho to shoot his new film ''[[Secret Child]]'' in 2017. The film is based on Gordon Lewis' bestselling book, ''Secret Child''. It starred [[Fiona Glascott]] ([[Brooklyn]], [[Fantastic Beasts: The Crimes of Grindelwald]]), Austin Taylor ([[My Cousin Rachel (2017 film)|My Cousin Rachel]], [[Doctor Who]]) and [[Aaron McCusker]] ([[Bohemian Rhapsody (film)|Bohemian Rhapsody]], [[Shameless (British TV series)|Shameless]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/culture/entertainment/secret-child-gordon-lewis|title=\"Secret Child\" - short film portrays pain of growing up in an Irish mother and babies home|date=2018-05-17|website=IrishCentral.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> ''Secret Child'' tells the true story in the 1950s that deals with a young boy hidden away from the world in a home for unmarried mothers called Regina Coeli in Dublin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25989021-secret-child|title=Secret Child|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.secretchild.com/the-story|title=Gordon Lewis {{!}} Official Website|last=|first=|date=|website=Secret Child|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> The film was a breakthrough success for Shu as it won more than 20 international awards. It had its world premiere at the [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre|Chinese Theatre]] in [[Hollywood]] at the [[HollyShorts Film Festival]] 2018 and receive a nomination for Best Period Piece.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hollyshorts.com/filmmakers-2018|title=Official Selections 2018 \u2014|website=www.hollyshorts.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> \n\nFor its London premiere at the New Renaissance Film Festival 2018, ''[[Secret Child]]'' won Best Debut Film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newrenaissancefilmfest.com/winners-nrff-london-2018|title=WINNERS \u2013 NEW RENAISSANCE LONDON 2018 \u00ab New Renaissance Film Festival|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Producer Gordon Lewis is currently in talks to turn ''Secret Child'' into a [[television series]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/showbiz/2018/06/08/uk-based-malaysian-cinematographer-earning-raves-with-film-on-secret-cathol/1640021|title=UK-based Malaysian cinematographer earning raves with film on secret Catholic hostel life {{!}} Malay Mail|last=Chalil|first=Melanie|website=www.malaymail.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/movies/movie-news/article36897505.ece|title=\u2018I couldn\u2019t have published this memoir if my mother was alive - it was too painful for her\u2019 - Irish man raised in mother and baby home|website=independent|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\nLater that year, Shu reunited with Kajri Babbar for her second television-film, [[ZEE5]] Original, ''Khoj'' (2018) filming in both UK and India with [[Bollywood]] actress Zara Khan.\n\nThe film premiered at [[Cannes Film Festival]] and went on to stream on [[ZEE5]], India's largest streaming channel[[Cannes Film Festival|.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/kajri-babbars-short-film-to-release-on-lohri/1456398|title=Kajri Babbar's short film to release on Lohri|website=www.outlookindia.com|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-zee5-announces-kajri-babbar-s-award-winning-short-film-khoj-2706987|title=ZEE5 announces Kajri Babbar's award winning short film 'Khoj'|last=Team|first=DNA Web|date=2019-01-12|website=DNA India|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n[[File:His hands Tribeca 3 (1).jpg|alt=|thumb|344x344px|Shu (left) with Arron Blake and Philip Brisebois at the red carpet premiere of ''His Hands'' at [[Tribeca Film Festival]] 2019, New York]]\nIn 2018, Shu team up with [[Arron Blake]] and they both co-directed, wrote, and produced ''[[His Hands (film)|His Hands]] (2019),'' with Shu shooting the film as the cinematographer. This was their directorial debut and the first film they made together starring Arron Blake and Philip Brisebois. ''His Hands'' had its world premiere at [[Robert De Niro]]'s [[Tribeca Film Festival]] 2019 in [[New York City|New York]]. The film received nomination for Best Narrative Short.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/film/2019/4/26/two-men-have-psychosexual-encounter-new-short-film|title=Two Men Have a Psychosexual Encounter in New Short Film|date=2019-04-26|website=www.advocate.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> The film created a whole new experience as it was a silent psychological thriller, using only the power of visual storytelling and cinematography.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{Cite web|url=http://attitude.co.uk/article/his-hands-review-an-erotic-and-unsettling-short-film-of-striking-power/19976/|title='His Hands' review: 'An erotic and unsettling short film of striking power'|date=2019-01-02|website=Attitude.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> It tells the story of two men meeting for the most unusual unanimity of their lives as it touches themes such as sexuality, loneliness, identity and ageism.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated3\" />  The film was applauded as a cinematic masterpiece as it was made on a low budget of \u00a3400, with no dialogue delivery throughout the film and using only natural light during filming.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.londonlive.co.uk/news/2019-05-16/film-with-budget-of-400-premiere-s|title=Film with budget of \u00a3400 premiered at world leading film festival|date=2019-05-16|website=London Live|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> The film was released on [[Prime Video|Amazon Prime Video]] and has received rave 5 star reviews from the public with critical acclaim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/His-Hands-Arron-Blake/product-reviews/B07WPG85QK/ref=cm_cr_dp_d_show_all_btm?ie=UTF8&reviewerType=all_reviews|title=Amazon.co.uk:Customer reviews: His Hands|website=www.amazon.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Shu team up to shoot a film with director [[Rikki Beadle-Blair|Rikki-Beadle Blair]], MBE. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BxrgHSvnu2z/|title=Bridge The Moon on Instagram: \u201cOur producers held our 1st meeting @bafta to kickstart pre-production for our upcoming film \u2018Tainted\u2019. \u2800 \u2800 Directed by the inimitable\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> He has also shot a commercial for [[Chanel]] and [[Coach New York|Coach]] where he was flown over to New York to film with seven celebrities from [[Southeast Asia|South East Asia]]. Shu attended Chanel's prestigious fashion show during [[Paris Fashion Week]] in France to shoot for Chanel with singer-songwriter [[Yuna (singer)|Yuna]] and The Laterals magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B3_0JUXl8ug/|title=DARIUS SHU on Instagram: \"ACT II: THE STREET \u2800 @chanelofficial @thelaterals featuring @yuna. \u2800 #HANDBAGCHANEL19 \u2800 \u2800 Cinematography by Darius Shu\u2800 Produced by\u2026\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\nLater that year, Shu reunited with director Yew Weng Ho on a new [[dyslexia]] film, ''Mical (2020)''. It follows the true story of Pat and Mike Jones on the struggles and journey of being dyslexic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.micalthefilm.com/|title=Mical {{!}} Official Film Site|website=Mical The Film|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> The film is to create awareness on dyslexia and to support the Dyslexia Trust.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.micalthefilm.com/|title=Mical {{!}} Official Film Site|website=Mical The Film|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Shu is currently working with [[Shiva Raichandani]] on his new British-Asian drama-musical film ''Queer Parivaar'' based on an interfaith queer wedding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.queerparivaar.co.uk/team|title=TEAM|website=Queer Parivaar|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n== Recognition ==\n\n[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]] magazine, reviewed Shu's film ''[[His Hands (film)|His Hands]] (2019)'' calling, \"the cinematography is beautiful, modern and stylish. ''His Hands'' is a powerful film that says a lot without \u201csaying\u201d anything at all. Its themes and images converge to create a stylish, dynamic thriller; Blake and Shu cleverly make use of colours, images, ideas in place of speech, and the film has a unique energy all the better for it.\"<ref name=autogenerated2 /> [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]] praised Shu as, \"a cinematographer who shoots to make things and people stand out.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/lifestyle/people/2018/06/27/cinematographer-darius-shu|title=Cinematographer Darius Shu shoots to make things and people stand out {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> [[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] magazine pointed out that, \"the cinematography of ''His Hands'' offers an unnerving experience through dark, haunting images with no dialogue.\"<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\n[[Mark Gatiss]], the producer of [[Netflix]]-[[BBC]] television series [[Dracula (2020 TV series)|Dracula]] and [[Sherlock (TV series)|Sherlock]], reviewed Shu's film ''His Hands'' as, ''\"A beguilingly beautiful gem, Arron Blake and Darius Shu's His Hands defies easy analysis. Shot through with strange, homoerotic melancholy it's ravishing to look at and haunts the memory long after.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldofbuzz.com/with-only-rm2000-msian-directors-debut-film-was-selected-for-robert-de-niros-film-festival/|title=This M\u2019sian Director\u2019s Debut Film Only Cost RM2,000 But Was Selected For Robert De Niro\u2019s Film Festival! - WORLD OF BUZZ|last=Ng|first=Scott|date=2019-05-01|website=www.worldofbuzz.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/lifestyle/entertainment/2019/04/30/darius-shu-his-hands-tribeca-film-festival|title=Malaysian Darius Shu's 'His Hands' goes to NY's Tribeca Film Fest {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\nFilm Threat praised Shu's work as, \"glorious cinematography, beautifully well shot, exuding a mysterious atmosphere in each frame\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/his-hands/|title=His Hands {{!}} Film Threat|date=2019-04-27|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> while Unsettled Magazine called ''His Hands'', \"a masterpiece built on suspense and appealing imagery.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/entertainmentmovies/malaysian-co-directed-low-budget-silent-film-makes-debut-in-new-yorks-tribeca-film-festival/ar-BBWoply?li=AAaD1A0|title=Malaysian co-directed, low-budget silent film makes debut in New York\u2019s Tribeca Film Festival|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\nUK Film Review stated that there were \"splendid visual moments\" in ''His Hands'' and \"Shu turns in some excellent cinematography as well as some clever framing.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukfilmreview.co.uk/post/his-hands-short-film|title=His Hands short film|last=Olson|first=Chris|date=2018-11-13|website=UK Film Review|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nShu made his first live television appearance in an interview on [[London Live (TV channel)|London Live]] after the success of [[Tribeca Film Festival]].<ref name=autogenerated1 /> He has also appeared in an extensive newspaper coverage in the mainstream media in [[Southeast Asia|South East Asia]] and the UK.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dariusshu.com/news|title=News {{!}} DARIUS SHU {{!}} Director of Photography|website=dariusshu 2.0|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n'''Films'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Director\n!Notes\n|-\n|2016\n|''Grief''\n|Caspar Muller\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\n|-\n|2016\n|''Bulletproof''\n|Darius Shu \n|-\n|2016\n|''Pardaa''\n|Kajri Babbar\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''White Balance: The Grape''\n|Tashita Mukherji\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''Narcissus Revisited''\n|Caspar Muller\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''Secret Child''\n|Yewweng Ho\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''Khoj''\n|Kajri Babbar\n|TV movie\n|-\n|2019\n|''His Hands''\n|Arron Blake, Darius Shu\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''Tainted''\n|[[Rikki Beadle-Blair]]\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''Mical''\n|Yewweng Ho\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''Queer Parivaar''\n|[[Shiva Raichandani]] \n|\n|-\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n\n=== Film festivals ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Festival\n!Category\n!Work\n!Result\n|-\n|2017\n|Aesthetica Short Film Festival\n|Nahemi Short Film Award \n| rowspan=\"3\" |''Pardaa''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2017\n|Calcutta International Cult Film Festival\n|Best Short Film\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2017\n|Sydney Indie Film Festival\n|Best Drama\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n|[[HollyShorts Film Festival|Hollyshorts Film Festival]]\n|Best Period Piece\n| rowspan=\"15\" |''Secret Child''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|Alternative Film Festival\n|Best Period Piece\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2018\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Los Angeles Independent Film Festival Awards\n|Best Cinematography\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n|Best Drama Short\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|New Renaissance Film Festival\n|Best Debut Film\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2018\n|Gold Movie Awards\n|Best Short Film\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Festigious International Film Festival\n|Best Cinematography\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Narrative Short\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2018\n|European Cinematography Awards\n|Best Short Film\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Bucharest ShortCut Cinefest\n|Best Cinematography\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Film\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2018\n|Kerry Film Festival\n|Best Short Film\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2018\n|Largo Film Awards\n|Best Cinematography\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2018\n|Oniros Film Awards\n|Best Cinematography\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2018\n|Sydney Indie Film Festival\n|Best Film\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2018\n|Cefal\u00f9 Film Festival\n|Best Short Film\n|''Bulletproof''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Cannes Film Festival]]\n|Short Film Corner\n|''Khoj''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2018\n|Gold Movie Awards\n|Best Cinematography\n| rowspan=\"6\" |''His Hands''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Tribeca Film Festival]]\n|Best Narrative Short\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2019\n|Canada Shorts Film Festival\n|Award of Excellence\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2019\n|London International Motion Pictures Award\n|Best Narrative / Fiction UK Short Film\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2019\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Queen Palm International Film Festival\n|Best Cinematography \n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Best Short Film - Silent|Best Short Film - Silent\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2020\n|Maryland International Film Festival\n|Best Short Film\n|''Mical''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm8954266/?ref_=ttfc_fc_cr5 Darius Shu] on [[IMDb|IMDB]]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/dariusshu5 Darius Shu] on [[Instagram]]\n* [https://www.twitter.com/dariusshu Darius Shu] on [[Twitter]]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/dariusshu Darius Shu] on [[Facebook]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shu, Darius}}\n\n[[Category: 1994 births]]\n[[Category:English cinematographers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Film directors from London]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:People from London]]\n[[Category:British cinematographers]]\n", "name_user": "Kg668", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Darius_Shu"}
{"title_page": "Bernard Hale (priest)", "text_new": "[[File:Bernard Hale Peterhouse.jpg|thumb|Bernard Hale]]\n'''Bernard Hale''' (died 29 March 1663) was a 17th-century English clergyman and academic, who served as [[Archdeacon of Ely]] and Master of [[Peterhouse, Cambridge]].\n\nHale was the sixth son of William Hale of [[King's Walden]], Hertfordshire. THe Hale family had  made a fortune in London in the grocery business  in the previous century and then settled in Saffron Walden, where they were still living in Victorian times.<ref name=\"alum-cantab\"/>\n\nHe was educated at [[Richard Hale School]] in [[Hertford]]<ref name=\"RH School\">{{cite web|website=Richard Hale School|title=The Peterhouse Connection|url=http://www.richardhale.herts.sch.uk/welcome-to-rha/the-peterhouse-connection/|access-date=12 November 2019}}</ref> (founded by his grandfather Richard Hale in 1617), and at [[Peterhouse, Cambridge]]. He entered Peterhouse in 1625, graduating [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] 1629, [[Master of Arts (Oxford, Cambridge, and Dublin)|M.A.]] 1632, [[Bachelor of Divinity|B.D.]] (''[[per lit. reg.]]'') 1639, [[Doctor of Divinity|D.D.]] (''per lit. reg.'') 1660.<ref name=\"alum-cantab\">{{acad|id=HL625B|name=Hale, Bernard}}</ref>\n\nHe was a Fellow of Peterhouse 1632\u201334,<ref name=\"alum-cantab\"/> resigning the fellowship on the death of his father, which left him with a plentiful inheritance. He lived in [[London]] then [[Norfolk]], using his resources to provide for the local poor and for exhibitions for university students.<ref name=\"Beaumont\">{{cite magazine|last=Beaumont|first=Joseph|orig-year={{circa|1663}}|title=Ecclesiastical History: Some Account of Bernard Hale, D.D.|magazine=The Christian Remembrancer|year=1822|volume=4|pages=208\u2013209|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=b7URAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA208|access-date=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt [[the Restoration]] in 1660, Hale became [[Archdeacon of Ely]], a prebendary of [[Ely Cathedral]], Rector of [[Fen Ditton]] and Master of Peterhouse.<ref name=\"alum-cantab\"/>\n\nIn 1663 Hale was \"seized with a paralytic stupor\" for three days,<ref name=\"Beaumont\"/> dying on 29 March 1663. He was buried the following day, in the chapel of Peterhouse.<ref name=\"alum-cantab\"/>\n\nHe was a considerable benefactor to Peterhouse both in his lifetime and in his will, bequeathing land valued at more than \u00a37,000, endowing the organ scholarship, and providing for seven other scholarships.<ref name=\"RH School\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box\n |title=Master of [[Peterhouse, Cambridge]]\n |years=1660\u20131663\n |before=[[John Cosin]]\n |after=[[Joseph Beaumont]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Archdeacons of Ely}}\n{{Masters of Peterhouse, Cambridge}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hale, Bernard}}\n[[Category:1663 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Peterhouse, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Peterhouse, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Masters of Peterhouse, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Archdeacons of Ely]]\n[[Category:17th-century English Anglican priests]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Bernard Hale Peterhouse.jpg|thumb|Bernard Hale]]\n'''Bernard Hale''' (died 29 March 1663) was a 17th-century English clergyman and academic, who served as [[Archdeacon of Ely]] and Master of [[Peterhouse, Cambridge]].\n\nHale was the sixth son of William Hale of [[King's Walden]], Hertfordshire. THe Hale family had  made a fortune in London in the grocery business  in the previous century and then settled in Saffron Walden.<ref name=\"alum-cantab\"/>\n\nHe was educated at [[Richard Hale School]] in [[Hertford]]<ref name=\"RH School\">{{cite web|website=Richard Hale School|title=The Peterhouse Connection|url=http://www.richardhale.herts.sch.uk/welcome-to-rha/the-peterhouse-connection/|access-date=12 November 2019}}</ref> (founded by his grandfather Richard Hale in 1617), and at [[Peterhouse, Cambridge]]. He entered Peterhouse in 1625, graduating [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] 1629, [[Master of Arts (Oxford, Cambridge, and Dublin)|M.A.]] 1632, [[Bachelor of Divinity|B.D.]] (''[[per lit. reg.]]'') 1639, [[Doctor of Divinity|D.D.]] (''per lit. reg.'') 1660.<ref name=\"alum-cantab\">{{acad|id=HL625B|name=Hale, Bernard}}</ref>\n\nHe was a Fellow of Peterhouse 1632\u201334,<ref name=\"alum-cantab\"/> resigning the fellowship on the death of his father, which left him with a plentiful inheritance. He lived in [[London]] then [[Norfolk]], using his resources to provide for the local poor and for exhibitions for university students.<ref name=\"Beaumont\">{{cite magazine|last=Beaumont|first=Joseph|orig-year={{circa|1663}}|title=Ecclesiastical History: Some Account of Bernard Hale, D.D.|magazine=The Christian Remembrancer|year=1822|volume=4|pages=208\u2013209|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=b7URAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA208|access-date=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt [[the Restoration]] in 1660, Hale became [[Archdeacon of Ely]], a prebendary of [[Ely Cathedral]], Rector of [[Fen Ditton]] and Master of Peterhouse.<ref name=\"alum-cantab\"/>\n\nIn 1663 Hale was \"seized with a paralytic stupor\" for three days,<ref name=\"Beaumont\"/> dying on 29 March 1663. He was buried the following day, in the chapel of Peterhouse.<ref name=\"alum-cantab\"/>\n\nHe was a considerable benefactor to Peterhouse both in his lifetime and in his will, bequeathing land valued at more than \u00a37,000, endowing the organ scholarship, and providing for seven other scholarships.<ref name=\"RH School\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box\n |title=Master of [[Peterhouse, Cambridge]]\n |years=1660\u20131663\n |before=[[John Cosin]]\n |after=[[Joseph Beaumont]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Archdeacons of Ely}}\n{{Masters of Peterhouse, Cambridge}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hale, Bernard}}\n[[Category:1663 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Peterhouse, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Peterhouse, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Masters of Peterhouse, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Archdeacons of Ely]]\n[[Category:17th-century English Anglican priests]]\n", "name_user": "Chrisdoyleorwell", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernard_Hale_(priest)"}
{"title_page": "Gentleman Adventurers of Fife", "text_new": "The '''Gentleman Adventurers of Fife''' or '''Fife Adventurers''' were a group of 11 noblemen-colonists, largely from eastern [[Fife]], awarded rights from [[King James VI]] to colonise the [[Isle of Lewis]] in 1598.\n\n==Background==\n\nIn 1597 the [[Clan MacLeod|MacLeod]] clan chiefs were served with papers from the government stating that despite their centuries long tenure of the [[Isle of Lewis]] their lack of legal paperwork exposed the lands to claims from the Crown. This stemmed from an [[List of Acts of the Scottish Parliament to 1707|Act of Parliament]] requiring all [[Scottish Highlands|Highland]] clan [[Scottish clan#Inheritance and authority|chiefs]] to prove legal ownership of their land.<ref name=\"keay\">{{cite book|last=Keay|first=John & Julia|title=Collins Encyclopedia of Scotland|year=1994|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-00-255082-6|page=370}}</ref> \n\nThis head-over-heels legislation exposed many long-held ancestral lands to seizure. The generally title-less lands of the highlands and islands became a target for the more document-conscious Lowlanders. Legally trained nobility were the first to take opportunity of this, creating papers for lands with which they had no historical connection.\n\n==The Re-Colonisation of Lewis==\n\nKing James had the aim of beginning the \"civilising\" or \"de-[[Gaelicisation]]\" of the islands and had much in common with the [[Plantation of Ulster]] which occurred some years later. James regarded the need for civilisation as sufficiently important to employ \"slauchter, mutilation, fyre-raising, or utheris inconvenieties\" if necessary.<ref name=\"haswell-smith\">{{cite book|last=Haswell-Smith|first=Hamish|title=The Scottish Islands|year=1996|publisher=Canongate|isbn=978-0-86241-579-2|pages=240\u2013241}}</ref> In fact, he had initially planned to murder all of the native inhabitants in order to facilitate settlement, but was persuaded to abandon this plan as impractical.<ref>Lenihan, P\u00e1draig. 2008.Consolidating Conquest: Ireland 1603-1727. Harlow: Longman. Pages 43-44.</ref>\n\nMost notable were the Gentleman Adventurers. In 1598 a group of noblemen, several from east Fife, sought the approval of [[King James VI]] for the colonization of the Isle of Lewis.  This had at its core a concept to exploit the island\u2019s natural resources. The noblemen were [[Patrick Leslie, 1st Lord Lindores|Patrick Leslie]] of [[Lindores Abbey|Lindores]], James Learmonth of [[Balcomie]], Sir [[James Anstruther]], Master of Household to [[Anne of Denmark]], [[James Spens (diplomat)|James Spens of Wormieston]], [[James Sandilands (courtier)|Sir James Sandilands]] of [[Slamannan]], Cpt William Murray, John Forret of [[Fingask, Fife|Fingask]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fife-placenames.glasgow.ac.uk/placename/?id=2728 |title=Fife Place-name Data :: Fingask |publisher=Fife-placenames.glasgow.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> [[William Stewart of Houston|Sir William Stewart]], [[Commendator of Pittenweem]], [[George Home (Comptroller of Scotland)|Sir George Home]] of [[Wedderburn Castle|Wedderburn]] and his son David Home, and the [[Ludovic Stewart, 2nd Duke of Lennox|Duke of Lennox]], the king\u2019s cousin.<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1592-1599'', vol. 5 (Edinburgh, 1882), pp. 462-3, 467-8.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=msu.31293027205800&view=1up&seq=573 |title=The register of the Privy Council of Scotland. v.5 1592-1599. - Full View &#124; HathiTrust Digital Library &#124; HathiTrust Digital Library |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2017-02-22 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc2.ark:/13960/t0pr7q77f&view=1up&seq=323 |title=Domestic annals of Scotland, from the reformation ... v.0001. - Full View &#124; HathiTrust Digital Library &#124; HathiTrust Digital Library |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2010-04-29 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nThe Gentlemen Adventurers of Fife arrived at the [[Isle of Lewis]] by ship from [[St Andrews]] in 1599 with a private army of 600 men.\n\nA settlement of primitive houses was created on the Lewis coast near where [[Stornoway]] now stands, in an area now called South Beach.\n\nThe Clan Macleod were feudal lords of Lewis and the then clan chief Roderick Macleod sent his sons, Neil and Murdoch, to harass the new settlers. Murdoch, in particular, was a man of much learning, and was trained in the law, rather than being an illiterate pagan as the settlers purported. He served the settlers with legal papers stating the illegality of their actions. Failing any action Murdoch attacked the settlement and captured their ship and James Learmonth whom he detained for 6 months.<ref>[[Sir Robert Gordon, 1st Baronet|Robert Gordon]], [https://archive.org/details/genealogicalhist00gord/page/270/mode/2up ''Genealogical history of the Earldom of Sutherland'' (Edinburgh, 1813), pp. 270-1.]</ref>\n\nSoon after Neil Macleod attacked the settlement with 200 men, killing 20 settlers, and seizing their property and livestock. A power struggle then began between the Macleod brothers and Neil agreed to surrender Murdoch to the remaining settlers in exchange for a pardon for his own crimes, in a court in Edinburgh. However, the agreement soured, and on return to Lewis he killed a further 60 settlers in anger.\n\nAlthough the Adventurers were forced to return to Fife, [[Kenneth Mackenzie, 1st Lord Mackenzie of Kintail|MacKenzie of Kintail]] a rival clan, was given free leave by the Crown to attack the island of Lewis in exchange for its land, and was pushed into hunting down Neil Macleod who was eventually captured on the island of [[Berisay]].\n\nNeil Macleod was taken to Edinburgh by ship and put on trial. On 30 March 1613 charged with fire-raising, murder, theft and piracy. He was hung  at the Mercat Cross on the [[Royal Mile]] on 1 April. He was not beheaded whilst alive (this punishment was for noblemen) but his head was removed post mortem and was placed on a spike above the Nether Bow Port. His lands were forfeited to the Crown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hebrideanconnections.com/subjects/36411|title=Neil Macleod &#124; Hebridean Connections|website=www.hebrideanconnections.com}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Anglicisation]]\n* [[Colonisation]]\n\n== External links==\n* [https://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/history/ssne/item.php?id=1642 Career of James Spens of Wormestoun, SPENS, JAMES [SSNE 1642].]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Human migration]]\n[[Category:Isle of Lewis]]\n[[Category:History of colonialism]]\n[[Category:People from Fife]]\n[[Category:1598 in Scotland]]\n\n{{hist-stub}}\n{{scotland-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Gentleman Adventurers of Fife''' or '''Fife Adventurers''' were a group of 11 noblemen-colonists, largely from eastern [[Fife]], awarded rights from [[King James VI]] to colonise the [[Isle of Lewis]] in 1598.\n\n==Background==\n\nIn 1597 the [[Clan MacLeod|MacLeod]] clan chiefs were served with papers from the government stating that despite their centuries long tenure of the [[Isle of Lewis]] their lack of legal paperwork exposed the lands to claims from the Crown. This stemmed from an [[List of Acts of the Scottish Parliament to 1707|Act of Parliament]] requiring all [[Scottish Highlands|Highland]] clan [[Scottish clan#Inheritance and authority|chiefs]] to prove legal ownership of their land.<ref name=\"keay\">{{cite book|last=Keay|first=John & Julia|title=Collins Encyclopedia of Scotland|year=1994|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-00-255082-6|page=370}}</ref> \n\nThis head-over-heels legislation exposed many long-held ancestral lands to seizure. The generally title-less lands of the highlands and islands became a target for the more document-conscious Lowlanders. Legally trained nobility were the first to take opportunity of this, creating papers for lands with which they had no historical connection.\n\n==The Re-Colonisation of Lewis==\n\nKing James had the aim of beginning the \"civilising\" or \"de-[[Gaelicisation]]\" of the islands and had much in common with the [[Plantation of Ulster]] which occurred some years later. James regarded the need for civilisation as sufficiently important to employ \"slauchter, mutilation, fyre-raising, or utheris inconvenieties\" if necessary.<ref name=\"haswell-smith\">{{cite book|last=Haswell-Smith|first=Hamish|title=The Scottish Islands|year=1996|publisher=Canongate|isbn=978-0-86241-579-2|pages=240\u2013241}}</ref> In fact, he had initially planned to murder all of the native inhabitants in order to facilitate settlement, but was persuaded to abandon this plan as impractical.<ref>Lenihan, P\u00e1draig. 2008.Consolidating Conquest: Ireland 1603-1727. Harlow: Longman. Pages 43-44.</ref>\n\nMost notable were the Gentleman Adventurers. In 1598 a group of noblemen, several from east Fife, sought the approval of [[King James VI]] for the colonization of the Isle of Lewis.  This had at its core a concept to exploit the island\u2019s natural resources. The noblemen were [[Patrick Leslie, 1st Lord Lindores|Patrick Leslie]] of [[Lindores Abbey|Lindores]], James Learmonth of [[Balcomie]], Sir [[James Anstruther]], Master of Household to [[Anne of Denmark]], [[James Spens (diplomat)|James Spens of Wormieston]], [[James Sandilands (courtier)|Sir James Sandilands]] of [[Slamannan]], Cpt William Murray, John Forret of [[Fingask, Fife|Fingask]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fife-placenames.glasgow.ac.uk/placename/?id=2728 |title=Fife Place-name Data :: Fingask |publisher=Fife-placenames.glasgow.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> [[William Stewart of Houston|Sir William Stewart]], [[Commendator of Pittenweem]], [[George Home (Comptroller of Scotland)|Sir George Home]] of [[Wedderburn Castle|Wedderburn]] and his son David Home, and the [[Ludovic Stewart, 2nd Duke of Lennox|Duke of Lennox]], the king\u2019s cousin.<ref>David Masson, ''Register of the Privy Council of Scotland: 1592-1599'', vol. 5 (Edinburgh, 1882), pp. 462-3, 467-8.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=msu.31293027205800&view=1up&seq=573 |title=The register of the Privy Council of Scotland. v.5 1592-1599. - Full View &#124; HathiTrust Digital Library &#124; HathiTrust Digital Library |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2017-02-22 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc2.ark:/13960/t0pr7q77f&view=1up&seq=323 |title=Domestic annals of Scotland, from the reformation ... v.0001. - Full View &#124; HathiTrust Digital Library &#124; HathiTrust Digital Library |publisher=Babel.hathitrust.org |date=2010-04-29 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nThe Gentlemen Adventurers of Fife arrived at the [[Isle of Lewis]] by ship from [[St Andrews]] in 1599 with a private army of 600 men.\n\nA settlement of primitive houses was created on the Lewis coast near where [[Stornoway]] now stands, in an area now called South Beach.\n\nThe Clan Macleod were feudal lords of Lewis and the then clan chief Roderick Macleod sent his sons, Neil and Murdoch, to harass the new settlers. Murdoch, in particular, was a man of much learning, and was trained in the law, rather than being an illiterate pagan as the settlers purported. He served the settlers with legal papers stating the illegality of their actions. Failing any action Murdoch attacked the settlement and captured their ship and James Learmonth whom he detained for 6 months.\n\nSoon after Neil Macleod attacked the settlement with 200 men, killing 20 settlers, and seizing their property and livestock. A power struggle then began between the Macleod brothers and Neil agreed to surrender Murdoch to the remaining settlers in exchange for a pardon for his own crimes, in a court in Edinburgh. However, the agreement soured, and on return to Lewis he killed a further 60 settlers in anger.\n\nAlthough the Adventurers were forced to return to Fife, [[Kenneth Mackenzie, 1st Lord Mackenzie of Kintail|MacKenzie of Kintail]] a rival clan, was given free leave by the Crown to attack the island of Lewis in exchange for its land, and was pushed into hunting down Neil Macleod who was eventually captured on the island of [[Berisay]].\n\nNeil Macleod was taken to Edinburgh by ship and put on trial. On 30 March 1613 charged with fire-raising, murder, theft and piracy. He was hung  at the Mercat Cross on the [[Royal Mile]] on 1 April. He was not beheaded whilst alive (this punishment was for noblemen) but his head was removed post mortem and was placed on a spike above the Nether Bow Port. His lands were forfeited to the Crown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hebrideanconnections.com/subjects/36411|title=Neil Macleod &#124; Hebridean Connections|website=www.hebrideanconnections.com}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Anglicisation]]\n* [[Colonisation]]\n\n== External links==\n* [https://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/history/ssne/item.php?id=1642 Career of James Spens of Wormestoun, SPENS, JAMES [SSNE 1642].]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Human migration]]\n[[Category:Isle of Lewis]]\n[[Category:History of colonialism]]\n[[Category:People from Fife]]\n[[Category:1598 in Scotland]]\n\n{{hist-stub}}\n{{scotland-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe Re-Colonisation of Lewis:ref: and major source.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gentleman_Adventurers_of_Fife"}
{"title_page": "Ukraine International Airlines", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{redirect|Ukraine Airlines||List of airlines of Ukraine}}\n{{Infobox airline\n|airline=Ukraine International Airlines (UIA) <br><small>{{lang|uk|\u041c\u0456\u0436\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0456 \u0410\u0432\u0456\u0430\u043b\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0457 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 (\u041c\u0410\u0423)}}</small>\n|logo=Ukraine International Airlines Logo.svg\n|logo_size=200\n|image=\n|IATA=PS\n|ICAO=AUI\n|callsign=UKRAINE INTERNATIONAL\n|aoc=\n|focus_cities=|frequent_flyer=Panorama Club\n|alliance=\n|hubs = [[Boryspil_International_Airport|Kiev\u2013Boryspil]]\n|fleet_size=35\n|destinations=88\n|parent={{nowrap|Capital Investment Project LLC (74%)}}\n|num_employees=\n|founded=1 October 1992\n|headquarters=[[Kiev]], [[Ukraine]]\n|key_people={{nowrap|Evgeny Dykhne, President<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flyuia.com/eng/company/ukraine-international-airlines/uia/management-team.html|title=UIA Management Team - Ukraine International Airlines (UIA)|accessdate=24 April 2015}}</ref>}}\n|lounge=\n|website= {{official URL}}\n}}\n\n'''Ukraine International Airlines [[Joint Stock Company|PJSC]]''', often shortened to '''UIA''' ({{lang-uk|\u0410\u0432\u0456\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0456\u044f \u041c\u0456\u0436\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0456 \u0410\u0432\u0456\u0430\u043b\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0457 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438|Aviakompaniya Mizhnarodni Avialiniyi Ukrayiny}}, {{IPA-uk|\u02cc\u0251wij\u0250kom\u02c8p\u0251n\u207d\u02b2\u207eij\u0250 mi\u0292n\u0250\u02c8r\u0254dn\u207d\u02b2\u207ei \u02cc\u0251wij\u0250\u02c8l\u207d\u02b2\u207ein\u207d\u02b2\u207eiji \u028akr\u0250\u02c8jin\u026a|IPA}}), is the [[flag carrier]] and the largest [[airline]] of [[Ukraine]],<ref>\"[https://www.whichairline.com/airlines/ukraine-international-airlines Ukraine International Airlines].\"</ref> with its head office in [[Kiev]]<ref>\"[https://www.flyuia.com/eng/company/ukraine-international-airlines/Contacts.html Contact Ukraine International Airlines].\" Ukraine International Airlines. Retrieved on 21 June 2010. \"ADDRESS: UKRAINE INTERNATIONAL AIRLINES 201-203, Kharkivske Road, Kiev, 02121, Ukraine\"</ref> and its main hub at Kiev's [[Boryspil International Airport]]. It operates domestic and international passenger flights and cargo services to Europe, the Middle East, the United States,<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/content/business/ukraine-international-airlines-launches-direct-kyiv-new-york-city-flights-350928.html|title=Ukraine International Airlines launches direct Kyiv\u2013New York flights|work=KyivPost|accessdate=24 April 2015}}</ref> Canada,<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|last1=Liu|first1=Jim|title=Ukraine International plans Toronto launch in June 2018|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/275955/ukraine-international-plans-toronto-launch-in-june-2018/|accessdate=29 November 2017|work=Routesonline|date=29 November 2017}}</ref> and Asia.\n\n== History ==\n=== Early history ===\n[[File:18bg_-_Ukraine_International_Airlines_Boeing_737-2T4;_UR-GAD@FRA;01.04.1998_(5618455191).jpg|thumb|A Ukraine International Airlines [[Boeing 737-200]] in 1998]] \nEstablished {{by whom?|date=January 2020}} on 1 October 1992, the airline started operations on 25 November 1992 with a Kiev-[[London]] flight. It became one of the first \"joint ventures with foreign capital\" in Ukraine and the first airline in the [[former Soviet Union]] to use new [[Boeing 737 Classic#737-400|Boeing 737-400]] aircraft.{{citation needed|date= May 2017}} The founding shareholders were the Ukrainian Association of Civil Aviation and [[Guinness Peat Aviation]] (GPA), an Irish aircraft-leasing company.\n\nThe airline began [[cargo airline |cargo]] operations with a [[Boeing 737#737-200|Boeing 737-200]] aircraft on 13 November 1994 to [[London]] and [[Amsterdam]].\n\nIn 1996 [[Austrian Airlines]] and [[Swissair]] became shareholders, investing US$9&nbsp;million in new equity.{{citation needed|date= May 2017}}\n\nIn 2000 the [[European Bank for Reconstruction and Development]] became a shareholder by investing $5.4&nbsp;million. In 2006 UIA adopted a new classification-system for freight operations{{clarify|date= September 2013}} which allowed the airline to carry a wider range of goods, ranging from live animals to fresh food and valuable objects. Additionally, an express service was introduced to meet the needs of customers wishing to make use of expedited cargo-delivery services.{{citation needed|date= May 2017}}\n\n=== Developments since 2013 ===\n[[File:Boeing_777-2Q8_(ER)_-_Ukraine_International_Airlines_-_UR-GOA_SA0000118826.jpg|Ukraine International Airlines' first [[Boeing 777#777-200ER|Boeing 777-200ER]] delivered in February 2018|thumb]]\n[[File:UR-GAN_(2701347282).jpg|thumb|A former Ukraine International [[Boeing 737-300]] which has been retired in 2019]]\nIn the first half of 2013, the airline's traffic rose by 60% to {{nts|2,200,000 }} passengers. According to the company's president Yuri Miroshnikov, the UIA planned to achieve the same 2013 yearly results (i.e. to reach yearly traffic of {{nts|4,400,000}}).<ref name=\"\u041c\u0410\u0423 \u043f\u043e\u0445\u0432\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c\">{{cite news | url=http://pda.korrespondent.net/business/companies/1585315-mau-pohvastalas-rostom-passazhiropotoka-i-planami-nachat-polety-v-ssha | script-title=uk:\u041c\u0410\u0423 \u043f\u043e\u0445\u0432\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043c \u043f\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0430\u0436\u0438\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0442\u043e\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u0442\u044c \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u044b \u0432 \u0421\u0428\u0410 | work=[[Korrespondent.net]] | date=26 July 2013 | agency=[[UNIAN]] | accessdate=15 September 2013 | language=uk}}</ref> On 25 April 2014, UIA began non-stop flights from Kiev to [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] in [[New York City]].<ref name=UIA-NYC>{{cite web|url=https://www.flyuia.com/eng/company/ukraine-international-airlines/press/news/1658.html?news=1568&category=1|title=UIA opened ticket sales for Kiev \u2013 New York non-stop scheduled service|publisher=Ukraine International Airlines|accessdate=23 February 2014}}</ref> Also in 2013, due to the demise of competitor [[Aerosvit]], UIA launched new flights from Ukraine to [[Baku]] in [[Azerbaijan]], [[Yerevan]] in [[Armenia]], [[Larnaca]] in [[Cyprus]], [[Munich]] in [[Germany]], [[Warsaw]] in [[Poland]], [[Vilnius]] in [[Lithuania]], [[Prague]] in the [[Czech Republic]], [[Athens]] in [[Greece]], [[Batumi]] in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], [[Moscow]] ([[Moscow Sheremetyevo Airport|Sheremetyevo Airport]]), [[Yekaterinburg]], [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Kaliningrad]], [[Nizhnevartovsk]], [[Novosibirsk]], [[Rostov-on-Don]], and [[Sochi]] in [[Russia]], [[Bishkek]] in [[Kyrgyzstan]], and in 2014, [[New York City]] in the [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flyuia.com/ua/en/404|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429075624/http://www.flyuia.com/enews_landings/landing-page-for-new-routes/en.html|url-status=dead|title=New Flights from Kiev to Azerbaijan, Armenia, Cyprus, Poland, Lithuania, Czech Republic, Greece, Georgia, Russia, and Kyrgyzstan on flyUIA.com!|archivedate=29 April 2014|website=FlyUIA}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015 UIA was banned by Russian government from flying to Russian destinations as a response to a ban by Ukrainian government of Russian airlines from flying into Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/25/russia-and-ukraine-suspend-direct-flights-between-countries|title=Russia and Ukraine suspend direct flights between countries|first=Agence France-Presse in|last=Kiev|date=25 October 2015|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\nSince June 2016 most of UIA's international flights are sold with the basic \"hand luggage-only tariff\". If passengers are booking this tariff and want to check in luggage, fees up to US$60 per flight will be charged.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flyuia.com/eng/company/ukraine-international-airlines/press/news/1658.html?news=2879&category=1|title=Official site of UIA \u2013 Ukraine International Airlines (UIA) (Ukraine)|website=FlyUIA|access-date=22 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117064849/http://www.flyuia.com/eng/company/ukraine-international-airlines/press/news/1658.html?news=2879&category=1|archive-date=17 November 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Also since summer 2016 UIA [[wetlease]]s an [[Embraer ERJ 145 family|ERJ 145]] from [[Dniproavia]] (also of the group \"Privat\") for daily services to [[Chernivtsi International Airport|Chernivtsi]] (because the condition of the airport doesn't allow E-190 and B737-operations)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/47241-ukraine-intl-airlines-to-wet-lease-an-erj-145-this-summer|title=Ukraine Int'l Airlines to wet-lease an ERJ-145 this summer|website=ch-aviation}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 June 2016 the offices of UIA were searched because of an investigation of the National Anti-Corruption Bureau of Ukraine concerning passenger fees not paid to the State Aviation Fund.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/article/content/ukraine-politics/one-airline-fights-to-retain-pre-eminence-in-ukraine-416501.html|title=One airline fights to retain pre-eminence in Ukraine - Jun. 16, 2016|date=16 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Ukraine International announced a fleet modernization plan. While the first of three pre-owned [[Boeing 777-200ER]] had already been delivered, the airline expects several new [[Boeing 737]] and [[Embraer 195]] aircraft during the year to replace the last [[Boeing 737 Classic]]s.<ref>[http://www.rusaviainsider.com/ukraine-international-airlines-adjusts-2018-fleet-expansion-plans/ rusaviainsider.com - Ukraine International Airlines adjusts 2018 fleet expansion plans] 22 March 2018</ref>\n\nUkraine International ceased being a member<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flyingblue.fr/en/partners/airline/airline-ukraine-international-airlines/presentation|title=Flying Blue - Ukraine International|website=flyingblue.fr}}</ref> of the [[Flying Blue]] rewards programme as of 1 January 2019. Ukraine International Airlines informs about the delay of 22 flights, which has occurred in the evening of 29 January at Boryspil Airport. The delays were caused by the failure in refueling aircraft with aviation fuel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flyuia.com/ua/en/news/2019/failure-of-fueling-at-boryspil-airport|title=UIA information about the failure of fueling at Boryspil Airporton 29 January 2019 \u2013 Ukraine International Airlines (UIA) (Ukraine)|website=FlyUIA}}</ref> UIA will continue to write losses with approximately 50m USD for 2019 and therefore implemented saving measures according to the new [[CEO]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unian.net/economics/transport/10707921-prezident-aviakompanii-mau-evgeniy-dyhne-ya-znayu-rabotu-kompanii-kak-partner-so-storony-aeroporta-i-znayu-kak-passazhir-mnogie-voprosy-v-kompanii-resheny-ne-v-polzu-komforta-passazhira.html|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u0430\u0432\u0438\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u041c\u0410\u0423 \u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0414\u044b\u0445\u043d\u0435: \u00ab\u042f \u0437\u043d\u0430\u044e \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u0443 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438, \u043a\u0430\u043a \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u043d\u0435\u0440 \u0441\u043e \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0430\u044d\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430, \u0438 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u044e, \u043a\u0430\u043a \u043f\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0430\u0436\u0438\u0440. \u041c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u044b \u0432 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0440\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u044b \u043d\u0435 \u0432 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0437\u0443 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0444\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0430\u0436\u0438\u0440\u0430\u00bb|website=www.unian.net}}</ref>\n\n== Corporate affairs ==\nIn February 2011, the Ukrainian government sold its 61.6% stake in UIA to three existing minority shareholders for UAH 287&nbsp;million&nbsp; (US$36.2&nbsp;million). As of 26 July 2013, the airline was owned by Ukraine-based Capital Investment Project LLC (74%) and [[Cyprus]]-based Ontobet Promotions Limited (26%). Capital Investment Process, in turn, is owned by Ontobet.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ch-aviation.ch/portal/news/15675-uia-now-under-control-of-cyprus-based-ontobet-promotions|title=UIA now under control of Cyprus based Ontobet Promotions|accessdate={{date|2013-7-26}}|publisher=ch-aviation}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smida.gov.ua/db/participant/14348681|title=List of shareholders of UIA (in Ukrainian)|accessdate={{date|2013-7-26}}|publisher=Ukrainian state register of shareholders}}</ref> The owners are represented by Aron Mayberg, a business partner of [[Ihor Kolomoyskyi|Igor Kolomoyskyi]] and the former CEO of the bankrupt AeroSvit Airlines, from which partially licences and planes were transferred to Ukraine International Airlines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=51663044&privcapId=27721200&previousCapId=27721200&previousTitle=AeroSvit+Airlines,+CJSC|title=Aron Mayberg: Executive Profile & Biography - Bloomberg|website=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\nAs of 22 June 2016, the ownership structure is registered as the following: 74.1627% Capital Investment Project, Ukraine and 15.9108% Ontobet Promotions Ltd, [[Cyprus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smida.gov.ua/db/participant/14348681|title=\u0410\u0422 \"\u041c\u0406\u0416\u041d\u0410\u0420\u041e\u0414\u041d\u0406 \u0410\u0412\u0406\u0410\u041b\u0406\u041d\u0406\u0407 \u0423\u041a\u0420\u0410\u0407\u041d\u0418\" - Smida|website=www.smida.gov.ua}}</ref>\n\nThis is the second year in a row that the company has made a loss, despite seeing growth in passengers. According to a February statement by company head Yuri Miroshnikov, UIA is struggling to stay profitable in the face of growing competition from budget airlines. In 2017, the company recorded a [[Ukrainian hryvnia|UAH]] 304 million loss.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/business/ukraine-international-airlines-net-loss-up-by-nine-times.html|title=Ukraine International Airlines loses nearly $100 million &#124; KyivPost - Ukraine's Global Voice|date=26 March 2019|website=KyivPost}}</ref>\n\nUkraine International Airlines posted a net loss of almost UAH 2.7 billion (about $100 million) in 2018, or about nine times more than it lost in 2017, Ukrainian media reported on 25 March, citing a UIA investor report.\n\nUkraine International Airlines (UIA), the country's national carrier, is to slow down its expansion plans in order to stabilise its financial performance and climb out of the red.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rusaviainsider.com/ukraines-flag-carrier-places-financial-stability-ahead-expansion/|title=Ukraine International places financial stability ahead of fleet expansion|date=8 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nYuri Miroshnikov is stepping down as president of Ukraine International Airlines (UIA) on 12 September after 15 years of managing Ukraine's national carrier and working for UIA since 1993. Evgeny Dykhne will take on the leadership role at UIA from 18 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Loss-making Ukraine International Airlines appoints new president |url=https://www.aerotime.aero/clement.charpentreau/23921-loss-making-ukraine-international-airlines-appoints-new-president |website=www.aerotime.aero |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New president for Ukraine International Airlines |url=http://www.rusaviainsider.com/new-president-ukraine-international-airlines/ |website=Russian Aviation Insider |date=10 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe head of the state air traffic regulator of Ukraine stated at 8.11.2019 that UIA would owe them actually 1 billion UAH of not paid fees and penalties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.epravda.com.ua/news/2019/11/8/653504/|title=\u0413\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0445\u0443 \u0440\u043e\u0437\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u043e \u0441\u0443\u043c\u0443 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0443 \u0430\u0432\u0456\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0456\u0457 \u041c\u0410\u0423|website=\u0415\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u0430}}</ref>\n\n== Destinations ==\n{{main|List of Ukraine International Airlines destinations}}\nUIA connects Ukraine to over 80 destinations in [[Europe]], [[Asia]] and the [[Middle East]], as well as to New York City<ref name=\"auto1\"/> and Toronto<ref name=\"auto\"/> from its base at [[Boryspil International Airport|Boryspil Airport]], and also operates domestic flights. UIA serves over 1000 flights per week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flyuia.com/rus/about/ukraine-international-airlines/mau/introduction.html|title=\u0418\u043d\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u043e \u041c\u0410\u0423 - Ukraine International Airlines (UIA)|website=www.flyuia.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref>\nUkraine International Airlines (UIA) was  forced to make some involuntary changes to its summer 2019 flight schedules, with reduced frequencies and capacity on some selected routes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rusaviainsider.com/b737-max-delays-force-uia-amend-flight-schedules/|title=B737 MAX delays force UIA to amend its flight schedules|date=5 April 2019}}</ref> Although not officially a [[budget airline]], many of UIA's worldwide flights are popular with travellers because of its low fares, they use [[Boryspil International Airport]] as a [[transport hub]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108141107/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-51029994\n|title=Iran plane crash: Ukraine International Airline jet crashes killing 176 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=8 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108141107/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-51029994 |archive-date=8 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nDue to ongoing losses, the airline suspended flights to Amman, Riga, Beijing and Minsk in November 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/business/uia-ceases-flights-to-amman-minsk-riga-suspends-flights-to-beijing-due-to-losses.html|title=UIA ceases flights to Amman, Minsk, Riga, suspends flights to Beijing due to losses &#124; KyivPost - Ukraine's Global Voice|date=25 October 2019|website=KyivPost}}</ref> From 2020, flights to Bangkok and Krakow will also be suspended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flyuia.com/ii/en/news/2019/uia-keeps-axing-flight-program|title=UIA keeps axing flight program \u2013 Ukraine International Airlines (UIA) (International)|website=FlyUIA}}</ref>\n\n=== Codeshare agreements ===\nUkraine International Airlines has [[codeshare agreement]]s with the following airlines:<ref name=\"CAPA Ukraine International Airlines profile\">{{cite web|url=http://centreforaviation.com/profiles/airlines/ukraine-international-airlines-ps |title=Profile on Ukraine International Airlines |website=CAPA|publisher=Centre for Aviation|access-date=2016-11-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103152716/http://centreforaviation.com/profiles/airlines/ukraine-international-airlines-ps |archive-date=2016-11-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Air Astana]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Ukraine International / Air Astana begins codeshare partnership from June 2019 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/284777/ukraine-international-air-astana-begins-codeshare-partnership-from-june-2019/ |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=Routesonline |date=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Air France]] \n* [[Air Moldova]]\n* [[airBaltic]] \n* [[Austrian Airlines]]\n* [[Azerbaijan Airlines]]\n* [[EgyptAir]]\n* [[Iberia (airline)|Iberia]]\n* [[KLM]] \n* [[TAP Air Portugal]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Liu|first1=Jim|title=TAP Air Portugal / Ukraine International expands codeshare routes in W17|url=http://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/275676/tap-air-portugal-ukraine-international-expands-codeshare-routes-in-w17/|accessdate=10 November 2017|work=Routesonline|date=10 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Liu|first1=Jim|title=TAP Air Portugal expands Ukraine International codeshare in S18|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/277773/tap-air-portugal-expands-ukraine-international-codeshare-in-s18/|accessdate=22 March 2018|work=Routesonline|date=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Turkish Airlines]] \n{{div col end}}\n\n== Fleet ==\n[[File:UR-PSC LLBG 06-12-2013-2.jpg|thumb|Ukraine International [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800]]]]\n[[File:UR-GOA_(30422601717).jpg|thumb|Ukraine International [[Boeing 777-200ER]]]]\n{{As of|2020|04}}, the Ukraine International Airlines fleet consists of the following aircraft:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flyuia.com/eng/company/ukraine-international-airlines/uia/fleet.html|title=UIA Fleet \u2013 Ukraine International Airlines (UIA) (Ukraine)|website=FlyUIA|date=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse;text-align:center\"\n|+ '''Ukraine International Airlines fleet'''\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" width=\"150px\" | Aircraft\n! rowspan=\"2\" width=\"75px\" | In service\n! rowspan=\"2\" width=\"50px\" | Orders\n! colspan=\"4\" | Passengers\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Notes\n|-\n! <abbr title=\"Business Class\">B</abbr>\n! <abbr title=\"Economy Premium Class\">E+</abbr>\n! <abbr title=\"Economy Class\">E</abbr>\n! Total\n|-\n|[[Boeing 737-800]]\n|19\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|186\n|186\n|\n|-\n|{{nowrap|[[Boeing 737 MAX 8]]}}\n|\u2014\n|4\n| colspan=\"4\" |<abbr title=\"To be announced\">TBA</abbr>\n|Deliveries postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.avianews.com/ukraine/2018/09/14/mau_737max_2019/|title=\u041c\u0410\u0423 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0438\u0442 Boeing 737 MAX \u0432 2019 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0443 {{!}} avianews.com|website=www.avianews.com|language=ru-RU|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Boeing 737-900ER]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|4\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\u2014\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\u2014\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\u2014\n|189\n|189\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\n|-\n|215\n|215\n|-\n|[[Boeing 767-300ER]]\n|4\n|\u2014\n|12\n|38\n|211\n|261\n|To be retired in 2020<ref name=\"\u041c\u0410\u0423 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0442 \u043b\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0430 Boeing 737 Classic \u0432 2018 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0443\">{{cite web|url=https://www.avianews.com/ukraine/2018/02/24/mau_withdraw_737classic/|title=\u041c\u0410\u0423 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0442 \u043b\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0430 Boeing 737 Classic \u0432 2018 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0443 - avianews.com|website=www.avianews.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Boeing 777-200ER]]\n|3\n|\u2014\n|21\n|16\n|324\n|361\n|\n|-\n|[[Embraer 190]]\n|5\n|\u2014\n|8\n|\u2014\n|96\n|104\n|\n|-\n|[[Embraer 195]]\n|2\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|116\n|116\n| \n|-\n!Total\n!37\n!4\n!colspan=\"6\"|\n|}\n</center>\n\n== Accidents and incidents ==\n* On 8 January 2020, [[Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752]] was shot down by the [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps]] (IRGC) of Iran shortly after takeoff from Tehran Imam Khomeini International Airport. The IRGC attributed it to human error. The aircraft involved, UR-PSR, was a three-year-old [[Boeing 737 Next Generation#737-800|Boeing 737-800]]. There were 176 passengers and crew on board with no survivors.<ref> [https://edition.cnn.com/middleeast/live-news/iran-plane-crash-live-intl-hnk/index.html \u201cUkrainian Boeing plane crashes in Iran, 176 people dead\u201d], \u2018\u2018[[CNN]]\u2019\u2019, 8 January 2020</ref>  The crash was the first fatal aviation incident for Ukraine International Airlines since beginning operations in 1992.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{citeweb|title=Iran plane crash: All 176 passengers killed as Ukraine Boeing 737 crashes near Tehran|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/08/iran-plane-crash-170-passengers-feared-dead-ukraine-boeing-737/|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=8 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108054218/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/08/iran-plane-crash-170-passengers-feared-dead-ukraine-boeing-737/|archive-date=8 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Transport in Ukraine]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat-inline|Ukraine International Airlines}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120104190747/http://mobile.flyuia.com/en Official website (mobile version)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portalbar|Ukraine|Companies|Aviation}}\n{{Airlines of Ukraine}}\n{{Association of European Airlines}}\n{{IATA members|cis}}\n\n[[Category:Airlines established in 1992]]\n[[Category:Airlines of Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Association of European Airlines members]]\n[[Category:Government-owned airlines]]\n[[Category:IATA members]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian brands]]\n[[Category:Privat Group]]\n[[Category:1992 establishments in Ukraine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{redirect|Ukraine Airlines||List of airlines of Ukraine}}\n{{Infobox airline\n|airline=Ukraine International Airlines (UIA) <br><small>{{lang|uk|\u041c\u0456\u0436\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0456 \u0410\u0432\u0456\u0430\u043b\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0457 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 (\u041c\u0410\u0423)}}</small>\n|logo=Ukraine International Airlines Logo.svg\n|logo_size=200\n|image=\n|IATA=PS\n|ICAO=AUI\n|callsign=UKRAINE INTERNATIONAL\n|aoc=\n|focus_cities=|frequent_flyer=Panorama Club\n|alliance=\n|hubs = [[Boryspil_International_Airport|Kiev\u2013Boryspil]]\n|fleet_size=35\n|destinations=88\n|parent={{nowrap|Capital Investment Project LLC (74%)}}\n|num_employees=\n|founded=1 October 1992\n|headquarters=[[Kiev]], [[Ukraine]]\n|key_people={{nowrap|Evgeny Dykhne, President<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flyuia.com/eng/company/ukraine-international-airlines/uia/management-team.html|title=UIA Management Team - Ukraine International Airlines (UIA)|accessdate=24 April 2015}}</ref>}}\n|lounge=\n|website= {{official URL}}\n}}\n\n'''Ukraine International Airlines [[Joint Stock Company|PJSC]]''', often shortened to '''UIA''' ({{lang-uk|\u0410\u0432\u0456\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0456\u044f \u041c\u0456\u0436\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0456 \u0410\u0432\u0456\u0430\u043b\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0457 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438|Aviakompaniya Mizhnarodni Avialiniyi Ukrayiny}}, {{IPA-uk|\u02cc\u0251wij\u0250kom\u02c8p\u0251n\u207d\u02b2\u207eij\u0250 mi\u0292n\u0250\u02c8r\u0254dn\u207d\u02b2\u207ei \u02cc\u0251wij\u0250\u02c8l\u207d\u02b2\u207ein\u207d\u02b2\u207eiji \u028akr\u0250\u02c8jin\u026a|IPA}}), is the [[flag carrier]] and the largest [[airline]] of [[Ukraine]],<ref>\"[https://www.whichairline.com/airlines/ukraine-international-airlines Ukraine International Airlines].\"</ref> with its head office in [[Kiev]]<ref>\"[https://www.flyuia.com/eng/company/ukraine-international-airlines/Contacts.html Contact Ukraine International Airlines].\" Ukraine International Airlines. Retrieved on 21 June 2010. \"ADDRESS: UKRAINE INTERNATIONAL AIRLINES 201-203, Kharkivske Road, Kiev, 02121, Ukraine\"</ref> and its main hub at Kiev's [[Boryspil International Airport]]. It operates domestic and international passenger flights and cargo services to Europe, the Middle East, the United States,<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/content/business/ukraine-international-airlines-launches-direct-kyiv-new-york-city-flights-350928.html|title=Ukraine International Airlines launches direct Kyiv\u2013New York flights|work=KyivPost|accessdate=24 April 2015}}</ref> Canada,<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|last1=Liu|first1=Jim|title=Ukraine International plans Toronto launch in June 2018|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/275955/ukraine-international-plans-toronto-launch-in-june-2018/|accessdate=29 November 2017|work=Routesonline|date=29 November 2017}}</ref> and Asia.\n\n== History ==\n=== Early history ===\n[[File:18bg_-_Ukraine_International_Airlines_Boeing_737-2T4;_UR-GAD@FRA;01.04.1998_(5618455191).jpg|thumb|A Ukraine International Airlines [[Boeing 737-200]] in 1998]] \nEstablished {{by whom?|date=January 2020}} on 1 October 1992, the airline started operations on 25 November 1992 with a Kiev-[[London]] flight. It became one of the first \"joint ventures with foreign capital\" in Ukraine and the first airline in the [[former Soviet Union]] to use new [[Boeing 737 Classic#737-400|Boeing 737-400]] aircraft.{{citation needed|date= May 2017}} The founding shareholders were the Ukrainian Association of Civil Aviation and [[Guinness Peat Aviation]] (GPA), an Irish aircraft-leasing company.\n\nThe airline began [[cargo airline |cargo]] operations with a [[Boeing 737#737-200|Boeing 737-200]] aircraft on 13 November 1994 to [[London]] and [[Amsterdam]].\n\nIn 1996 [[Austrian Airlines]] and [[Swissair]] became shareholders, investing US$9&nbsp;million in new equity.{{citation needed|date= May 2017}}\n\nIn 2000 the [[European Bank for Reconstruction and Development]] became a shareholder by investing $5.4&nbsp;million. In 2006 UIA adopted a new classification-system for freight operations{{clarify|date= September 2013}} which allowed the airline to carry a wider range of goods, ranging from live animals to fresh food and valuable objects. Additionally, an express service was introduced to meet the needs of customers wishing to make use of expedited cargo-delivery services.{{citation needed|date= May 2017}}\n\n=== Developments since 2013 ===\n[[File:Boeing_777-2Q8_(ER)_-_Ukraine_International_Airlines_-_UR-GOA_SA0000118826.jpg|Ukraine International Airlines' first [[Boeing 777#777-200ER|Boeing 777-200ER]] delivered in February 2018|thumb]]\n[[File:UR-GAN_(2701347282).jpg|thumb|A former Ukraine International [[Boeing 737-300]] which has been retired in 2019]]\nIn the first half of 2013, the airline's traffic rose by 60% to {{nts|2,200,000 }} passengers. According to the company's president Yuri Miroshnikov, the UIA planned to achieve the same 2013 yearly results (i.e. to reach yearly traffic of {{nts|4,400,000}}).<ref name=\"\u041c\u0410\u0423 \u043f\u043e\u0445\u0432\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c\">{{cite news | url=http://pda.korrespondent.net/business/companies/1585315-mau-pohvastalas-rostom-passazhiropotoka-i-planami-nachat-polety-v-ssha | script-title=uk:\u041c\u0410\u0423 \u043f\u043e\u0445\u0432\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043c \u043f\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0430\u0436\u0438\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0442\u043e\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u0442\u044c \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u044b \u0432 \u0421\u0428\u0410 | work=[[Korrespondent.net]] | date=26 July 2013 | agency=[[UNIAN]] | accessdate=15 September 2013 | language=uk}}</ref> On 25 April 2014, UIA began non-stop flights from Kiev to [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]] in [[New York City]].<ref name=UIA-NYC>{{cite web|url=https://www.flyuia.com/eng/company/ukraine-international-airlines/press/news/1658.html?news=1568&category=1|title=UIA opened ticket sales for Kiev \u2013 New York non-stop scheduled service|publisher=Ukraine International Airlines|accessdate=23 February 2014}}</ref> Also in 2013, due to the demise of competitor [[Aerosvit]], UIA launched new flights from Ukraine to [[Baku]] in [[Azerbaijan]], [[Yerevan]] in [[Armenia]], [[Larnaca]] in [[Cyprus]], [[Munich]] in [[Germany]], [[Warsaw]] in [[Poland]], [[Vilnius]] in [[Lithuania]], [[Prague]] in the [[Czech Republic]], [[Athens]] in [[Greece]], [[Batumi]] in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], [[Moscow]] ([[Moscow Sheremetyevo Airport|Sheremetyevo Airport]]), [[Yekaterinburg]], [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Kaliningrad]], [[Nizhnevartovsk]], [[Novosibirsk]], [[Rostov-on-Don]], and [[Sochi]] in [[Russia]], [[Bishkek]] in [[Kyrgyzstan]], and in 2014, [[New York City]] in the [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flyuia.com/ua/en/404|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429075624/http://www.flyuia.com/enews_landings/landing-page-for-new-routes/en.html|url-status=dead|title=New Flights from Kiev to Azerbaijan, Armenia, Cyprus, Poland, Lithuania, Czech Republic, Greece, Georgia, Russia, and Kyrgyzstan on flyUIA.com!|archivedate=29 April 2014|website=FlyUIA}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015 UIA was banned by Russian government from flying to Russian destinations as a response to a ban by Ukrainian government of Russian airlines from flying into Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/25/russia-and-ukraine-suspend-direct-flights-between-countries|title=Russia and Ukraine suspend direct flights between countries|first=Agence France-Presse in|last=Kiev|date=25 October 2015|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\nSince June 2016 most of UIA's international flights are sold with the basic \"hand luggage-only tariff\". If passengers are booking this tariff and want to check in luggage, fees up to US$60 per flight will be charged.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flyuia.com/eng/company/ukraine-international-airlines/press/news/1658.html?news=2879&category=1|title=Official site of UIA \u2013 Ukraine International Airlines (UIA) (Ukraine)|website=FlyUIA|access-date=22 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117064849/http://www.flyuia.com/eng/company/ukraine-international-airlines/press/news/1658.html?news=2879&category=1|archive-date=17 November 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Also since summer 2016 UIA [[wetlease]]s an [[Embraer ERJ 145 family|ERJ 145]] from [[Dniproavia]] (also of the group \"Privat\") for daily services to [[Chernivtsi International Airport|Chernivtsi]] (because the condition of the airport doesn't allow E-190 and B737-operations)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/47241-ukraine-intl-airlines-to-wet-lease-an-erj-145-this-summer|title=Ukraine Int'l Airlines to wet-lease an ERJ-145 this summer|website=ch-aviation}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 June 2016 the offices of UIA were searched because of an investigation of the National Anti-Corruption Bureau of Ukraine concerning passenger fees not paid to the State Aviation Fund.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/article/content/ukraine-politics/one-airline-fights-to-retain-pre-eminence-in-ukraine-416501.html|title=One airline fights to retain pre-eminence in Ukraine - Jun. 16, 2016|date=16 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Ukraine International announced a fleet modernization plan. While the first of three pre-owned [[Boeing 777-200ER]] had already been delivered, the airline expects several new [[Boeing 737]] and [[Embraer 195]] aircraft during the year to replace the last [[Boeing 737 Classic]]s.<ref>[http://www.rusaviainsider.com/ukraine-international-airlines-adjusts-2018-fleet-expansion-plans/ rusaviainsider.com - Ukraine International Airlines adjusts 2018 fleet expansion plans] 22 March 2018</ref>\n\nUkraine International ceased being a member<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flyingblue.fr/en/partners/airline/airline-ukraine-international-airlines/presentation|title=Flying Blue - Ukraine International|website=flyingblue.fr}}</ref> of the [[Flying Blue]] rewards programme as of 1 January 2019. Ukraine International Airlines informs about the delay of 22 flights, which has occurred in the evening of 29 January at Boryspil Airport. The delays were caused by the failure in refueling aircraft with aviation fuel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flyuia.com/ua/en/news/2019/failure-of-fueling-at-boryspil-airport|title=UIA information about the failure of fueling at Boryspil Airporton 29 January 2019 \u2013 Ukraine International Airlines (UIA) (Ukraine)|website=FlyUIA}}</ref> UIA will continue to write losses with approximately 50m USD for 2019 and therefore implemented saving measures according to the new [[CEO]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unian.net/economics/transport/10707921-prezident-aviakompanii-mau-evgeniy-dyhne-ya-znayu-rabotu-kompanii-kak-partner-so-storony-aeroporta-i-znayu-kak-passazhir-mnogie-voprosy-v-kompanii-resheny-ne-v-polzu-komforta-passazhira.html|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u0430\u0432\u0438\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u041c\u0410\u0423 \u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0414\u044b\u0445\u043d\u0435: \u00ab\u042f \u0437\u043d\u0430\u044e \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u0443 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438, \u043a\u0430\u043a \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u043d\u0435\u0440 \u0441\u043e \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0430\u044d\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430, \u0438 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u044e, \u043a\u0430\u043a \u043f\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0430\u0436\u0438\u0440. \u041c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u044b \u0432 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0440\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u044b \u043d\u0435 \u0432 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0437\u0443 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0444\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0430\u0436\u0438\u0440\u0430\u00bb|website=www.unian.net}}</ref>\n\n== Corporate affairs ==\nIn February 2011, the Ukrainian government sold its 61.6% stake in UIA to three existing minority shareholders for UAH 287&nbsp;million&nbsp; (US$36.2&nbsp;million). As of 26 July 2013, the airline was owned by Ukraine-based Capital Investment Project LLC (74%) and [[Cyprus]]-based Ontobet Promotions Limited (26%). Capital Investment Process, in turn, is owned by Ontobet.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ch-aviation.ch/portal/news/15675-uia-now-under-control-of-cyprus-based-ontobet-promotions|title=UIA now under control of Cyprus based Ontobet Promotions|accessdate={{date|2013-7-26}}|publisher=ch-aviation}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smida.gov.ua/db/participant/14348681|title=List of shareholders of UIA (in Ukrainian)|accessdate={{date|2013-7-26}}|publisher=Ukrainian state register of shareholders}}</ref> The owners are represented by Aron Mayberg, a business partner of [[Ihor Kolomoyskyi|Igor Kolomoyskyi]] and the former CEO of the bankrupt AeroSvit Airlines, from which partially licences and planes were transferred to Ukraine International Airlines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=51663044&privcapId=27721200&previousCapId=27721200&previousTitle=AeroSvit+Airlines,+CJSC|title=Aron Mayberg: Executive Profile & Biography - Bloomberg|website=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n\nAs of 22 June 2016, the ownership structure is registered as the following: 74.1627% Capital Investment Project, Ukraine and 15.9108% Ontobet Promotions Ltd, [[Cyprus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smida.gov.ua/db/participant/14348681|title=\u0410\u0422 \"\u041c\u0406\u0416\u041d\u0410\u0420\u041e\u0414\u041d\u0406 \u0410\u0412\u0406\u0410\u041b\u0406\u041d\u0406\u0407 \u0423\u041a\u0420\u0410\u0407\u041d\u0418\" - Smida|website=www.smida.gov.ua}}</ref>\n\nThis is the second year in a row that the company has made a loss, despite seeing growth in passengers. According to a February statement by company head Yuri Miroshnikov, UIA is struggling to stay profitable in the face of growing competition from budget airlines. In 2017, the company recorded a [[Ukrainian hryvnia|UAH]] 304 million loss.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/business/ukraine-international-airlines-net-loss-up-by-nine-times.html|title=Ukraine International Airlines loses nearly $100 million &#124; KyivPost - Ukraine's Global Voice|date=26 March 2019|website=KyivPost}}</ref>\n\nUkraine International Airlines posted a net loss of almost UAH 2.7 billion (about $100 million) in 2018, or about nine times more than it lost in 2017, Ukrainian media reported on 25 March, citing a UIA investor report.\n\nUkraine International Airlines (UIA), the country's national carrier, is to slow down its expansion plans in order to stabilise its financial performance and climb out of the red.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rusaviainsider.com/ukraines-flag-carrier-places-financial-stability-ahead-expansion/|title=Ukraine International places financial stability ahead of fleet expansion|date=8 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nYuri Miroshnikov is stepping down as president of Ukraine International Airlines (UIA) on 12 September after 15 years of managing Ukraine's national carrier and working for UIA since 1993. Evgeny Dykhne will take on the leadership role at UIA from 18 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Loss-making Ukraine International Airlines appoints new president |url=https://www.aerotime.aero/clement.charpentreau/23921-loss-making-ukraine-international-airlines-appoints-new-president |website=www.aerotime.aero |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New president for Ukraine International Airlines |url=http://www.rusaviainsider.com/new-president-ukraine-international-airlines/ |website=Russian Aviation Insider |date=10 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe head of the state air traffic regulator of Ukraine stated at 8.11.2019 that UIA would owe them actually 1 billion UAH of not paid fees and penalties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.epravda.com.ua/news/2019/11/8/653504/|title=\u0413\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0445\u0443 \u0440\u043e\u0437\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u043e \u0441\u0443\u043c\u0443 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0443 \u0430\u0432\u0456\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0456\u0457 \u041c\u0410\u0423|website=\u0415\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u0430}}</ref>\n\n== Destinations ==\n{{main|List of Ukraine International Airlines destinations}}\nUIA connects Ukraine to over 80 destinations in [[Europe]], [[Asia]] and the [[Middle East]], as well as to New York City<ref name=\"auto1\"/> and Toronto<ref name=\"auto\"/> from its base at [[Boryspil International Airport|Boryspil Airport]], and also operates domestic flights. UIA serves over 1000 flights per week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flyuia.com/rus/about/ukraine-international-airlines/mau/introduction.html|title=\u0418\u043d\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u043e \u041c\u0410\u0423 - Ukraine International Airlines (UIA)|website=www.flyuia.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref>\nUkraine International Airlines (UIA) was  forced to make some involuntary changes to its summer 2019 flight schedules, with reduced frequencies and capacity on some selected routes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rusaviainsider.com/b737-max-delays-force-uia-amend-flight-schedules/|title=B737 MAX delays force UIA to amend its flight schedules|date=5 April 2019}}</ref> Although not officially a [[budget airline]], many of UIA's worldwide flights are popular with travellers because of its low fares, they use [[Boryspil International Airport]] as a [[transport hub]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108141107/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-51029994\n|title=Iran plane crash: Ukraine International Airline jet crashes killing 176 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=8 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108141107/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-51029994 |archive-date=8 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nDue to ongoing losses, the airline suspended flights to Amman, Riga, Beijing and Minsk in November 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/business/uia-ceases-flights-to-amman-minsk-riga-suspends-flights-to-beijing-due-to-losses.html|title=UIA ceases flights to Amman, Minsk, Riga, suspends flights to Beijing due to losses &#124; KyivPost - Ukraine's Global Voice|date=25 October 2019|website=KyivPost}}</ref> From 2020, flights to Bangkok and Krakow will also be suspended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flyuia.com/ii/en/news/2019/uia-keeps-axing-flight-program|title=UIA keeps axing flight program \u2013 Ukraine International Airlines (UIA) (International)|website=FlyUIA}}</ref>\n\n=== Codeshare agreements ===\nUkraine International Airlines has [[codeshare agreement]]s with the following airlines:<ref name=\"CAPA Ukraine International Airlines profile\">{{cite web|url=http://centreforaviation.com/profiles/airlines/ukraine-international-airlines-ps |title=Profile on Ukraine International Airlines |website=CAPA|publisher=Centre for Aviation|access-date=2016-11-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103152716/http://centreforaviation.com/profiles/airlines/ukraine-international-airlines-ps |archive-date=2016-11-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Air Astana]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Ukraine International / Air Astana begins codeshare partnership from June 2019 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/284777/ukraine-international-air-astana-begins-codeshare-partnership-from-june-2019/ |accessdate=17 June 2019 |work=Routesonline |date=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Air France]] \n* [[Air Moldova]]\n* [[airBaltic]] \n* [[Austrian Airlines]]\n* [[Azerbaijan Airlines]]\n* [[EgyptAir]]\n* [[Iberia (airline)|Iberia]]\n* [[KLM]] \n* [[TAP Air Portugal]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Liu|first1=Jim|title=TAP Air Portugal / Ukraine International expands codeshare routes in W17|url=http://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/275676/tap-air-portugal-ukraine-international-expands-codeshare-routes-in-w17/|accessdate=10 November 2017|work=Routesonline|date=10 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Liu|first1=Jim|title=TAP Air Portugal expands Ukraine International codeshare in S18|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/277773/tap-air-portugal-expands-ukraine-international-codeshare-in-s18/|accessdate=22 March 2018|work=Routesonline|date=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Turkish Airlines]] \n{{div col end}}\n\n== Fleet ==\n[[File:UR-PSC LLBG 06-12-2013-2.jpg|thumb|Ukraine International [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800]]]]\n[[File:UR-GOA_(30422601717).jpg|thumb|Ukraine International [[Boeing 777-200ER]]]]\n{{As of|2020|04}}, the Ukraine International Airlines fleet consists of the following aircraft:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flyuia.com/eng/company/ukraine-international-airlines/uia/fleet.html|title=UIA Fleet \u2013 Ukraine International Airlines (UIA) (Ukraine)|website=FlyUIA|date=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse;text-align:center\"\n|+ '''Ukraine International Airlines fleet'''\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" width=\"150px\" | Aircraft\n! rowspan=\"2\" width=\"75px\" | In service\n! rowspan=\"2\" width=\"50px\" | Orders\n! colspan=\"4\" | Passengers\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Notes\n|-\n! <abbr title=\"Business Class\">B</abbr>\n! <abbr title=\"Economy Premium Class\">E+</abbr>\n! <abbr title=\"Economy Class\">E</abbr>\n! Total\n|-\n|[[Boeing 737-800]]\n|19\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|186\n|186\n|\n|-\n|{{nowrap|[[Boeing 737 MAX 8]]}}\n|\u2014\n|4\n| colspan=\"4\" |<abbr title=\"To be announced\">TBA</abbr>\n|Deliveries postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.avianews.com/ukraine/2018/09/14/mau_737max_2019/|title=\u041c\u0410\u0423 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0438\u0442 Boeing 737 MAX \u0432 2019 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0443 {{!}} avianews.com|website=www.avianews.com|language=ru-RU|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Boeing 737-900ER]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|4\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\u2014\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\u2014\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\u2014\n|189\n|189\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\n|-\n|215\n|215\n|-\n|[[Boeing 767-300ER]]\n|4\n|\u2014\n|12\n|38\n|211\n|261\n|To be retired in 2020<ref name=\"\u041c\u0410\u0423 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0442 \u043b\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0430 Boeing 737 Classic \u0432 2018 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0443\">{{cite web|url=https://www.avianews.com/ukraine/2018/02/24/mau_withdraw_737classic/|title=\u041c\u0410\u0423 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0442 \u043b\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0430 Boeing 737 Classic \u0432 2018 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0443 - avianews.com|website=www.avianews.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Boeing 777-200ER]]\n|3\n|\u2014\n|21\n|16\n|324\n|361\n|\n|-\n|[[Embraer 190]]\n|5\n|\u2014\n|8\n|\u2014\n|96\n|104\n|\n|-\n|[[Embraer 195]]\n|2\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|116\n|116\n| \n|-\n!Total\n!37\n!4\n!colspan=\"6\"|\n|}\n</center>\n\n== Accidents and incidents ==\n* On 8 January 2020, [[Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752]] was shot down shortly after takeoff from Tehran Imam Khomeini International Airport by the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps of Iran, which attributed it to human error. The aircraft involved, UR-PSR, was a three-year-old [[Boeing 737 Next Generation#737-800|Boeing 737-800]]. There were 176 passengers and crew on board with no survivors.<ref> [https://edition.cnn.com/middleeast/live-news/iran-plane-crash-live-intl-hnk/index.html \u201cUkrainian Boeing plane crashes in Iran, 176 people dead\u201d], \u2018\u2018[[CNN]]\u2019\u2019, 8 January 2020</ref>  The crash was the first fatal aviation incident for Ukraine International Airlines since beginning operations in 1992.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{citeweb|title=Iran plane crash: All 176 passengers killed as Ukraine Boeing 737 crashes near Tehran|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/08/iran-plane-crash-170-passengers-feared-dead-ukraine-boeing-737/|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=8 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108054218/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/08/iran-plane-crash-170-passengers-feared-dead-ukraine-boeing-737/|archive-date=8 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Transport in Ukraine]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat-inline|Ukraine International Airlines}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120104190747/http://mobile.flyuia.com/en Official website (mobile version)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portalbar|Ukraine|Companies|Aviation}}\n{{Airlines of Ukraine}}\n{{Association of European Airlines}}\n{{IATA members|cis}}\n\n[[Category:Airlines established in 1992]]\n[[Category:Airlines of Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Association of European Airlines members]]\n[[Category:Government-owned airlines]]\n[[Category:IATA members]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian brands]]\n[[Category:Privat Group]]\n[[Category:1992 establishments in Ukraine]]\n", "name_user": "Rui Gabriel Correia", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAccidents and incidents", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ukraine_International_Airlines"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Czech Republic", "text_new": "{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in the Czech Republic}}\n{{bare URLs|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Czech Republic\n| map1            = COVID-19 outbreak Czechia per capita cases map.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases per million residents by region\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Czech Republic]]\n| first_case      = Unknown\n| arrival_date    = 1 March 2020<br/>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days\n | month1 = 03\n | day1   = 1\n | year1  = 2020\n | month2 = \n | day2   = \n | year2  = }} ago)\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], Hubei, China via Italy\n| recovery_cases  = 527<ref name=\":0\"/>\n| deaths          = 147<ref name=\":0\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 6,059<ref name=\":0\"/>\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://onemocneni-aktualne.mzcr.cz/covid-19}}\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] saw its first three confirmed cases in the [[Czech Republic]] on 1 March 2020. On 12 March, the government declared a [[state of emergency]], for the first time in the country's modern history for the area of the entire country. On 16 March, the country closed its borders, forbade the entry of foreigners and issued a nationwide curfew. While originally planned until 24 March, the measures were later extended until 1 April<ref name=\"apnews\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio.cz/en/section/breaking/czech-republic-severely-limits-freedom-of-movement-in-order-to-slow-down-coronavirus-spread|title=Czech Republic goes into quarantine to slow down coronavirus spread|website=Radio Prague International|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> and then again until the end of State of Emergency<ref name=\"third travel ban\" /> which was extended by the [[Chamber of Deputies of the Czech Republic|Chamber of Deputies]] until 30 April 2020.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.psp.cz/eknih/2017ps/stenprot/043schuz/s043037.htm#h8 |title=P\u010cR, PS 2017 , 43. sch\u016fze, \u010d\u00e1st 37 (7. 4. 2020) |publisher=Psp.cz |date= |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCzech Republic started gradual easing of measures from 7 April 2020 onwards.<ref name=\"third travel ban\" /><ref name=\"sports allowed\" />\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |date= |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom |url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |date= |website=wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/The Czech Republic medical cases chart}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size:80%; float:right; clear:right; margin:0 0 0.5em 1em;\"\"\n|+COVID-19 cases in the Czech Republic<ref name=\":0\"/>\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Date\n! colspan=\"2\" | Confirmed\n! colspan=\"2\" | Recovered\n! colspan=\"2\" | Deaths\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Active<br / >cases\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Tested<br/>(Total)\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Detected<br/>ratio\n|-\n! New\n! Total\n! New\n! Total\n! New\n! Total\n|-\n! 28 February\n| 0 || 0\n| 0 || 0\n| 0 || 0\n| 0\n| 193\n| \n|-\n! 29 February\n| 0 || 0\n| 0 || 0\n| 0 || 0\n| 0\n| 200\n| \n|-\n! 1 March\n| 3 || 3\n| 0 || 0\n| 0 || 0\n| 3\n| 211\n| {{#expr:3/(